{"title_page": "Pandya dynasty", "text_new": "{{redirect| Pandya|the surname| Pande}}\n{{short description|Ancient Tamil dynasty}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|conventional_long_name = Pandya Empire\n|common_name        = Pandya Empire\n|era                = \n|year_start         = \n|year_end           = \n|p1                 = \n|p2                 = \n|s1                 = Delhi Sultanate\n|s2                 = Madurai Nayak dynasty\n|s3                 = Jaffna kingdom\n|s4                 = Sambuvaraya\n|image_map          = Pandya Kingdom (south India).png\n|image_map_caption  = Pandya Empire (12th\u201314th century CE)\n|official_languages = \n*[[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n*[[Sanskrit]]<ref>{{cite book |author=Upinder Singh |title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3lUIIYxWkEC&pg=PA46 |year=2008 |publisher=Pearson Education India |isbn=978-81-317-1120-0 |page=46 |quote=Kings of the Chola and Pandya dynasties also issued Tamil and bilingual Sanskrit\u2013Tamil inscriptions. }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=C. Sivaramamurti |title=L'Art en Inde |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WKgQAQAAMAAJ |year=1977|publisher=H. N. Abrams |isbn=978-0-8109-0630-3 |p=60 |quote=Thus the state language was Sanskrit whether the inscriptions were from the north or the south and whether the dynasty was Gupta, Vakatak[a], Vardhana, Maukhari, Pratihara, Paramara, Chandella, Pala, Sena, Gahadavala, Haihaya, Ganga, Pallava, Chola, Pandya, Chalukya, Rashtrakuta, or Vijayanagar[a]. Inscriptions were sometimes written in regional languages, but they invariably had a preface in Sanskrit. }}</ref>\n|capital            = \n*[[Madurai]] (till mid-14th century)<ref name=\":31\" />\n*[[Korkai]] (port, early historic)<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Classical Indo-Roman Trade|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2013/26-27/special-articles/classical-indo-roman-trade.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=48|issue=26\u201327}}</ref>\n*[[Tenkasi]] (mid-14th century\u2013end of the 16th century CE)<ref name=\":31\" />\n|religion           = [[Hinduism]]<br>[[Jainism]]\n|government_type    = Monarchy\n|leader1            = [[Kadungon]]\n|year_leader1       = 560\u2013590 CE\n|leader2            = \"Five Pandyas\"\n|year_leader2       = 1100\u20131400 CE\n|today              = [[India]]<br />[[Sri Lanka]]\n|demonym            = \n|area_km2           = \n|area_rank          = \n|GDP_PPP            = \n|GDP_PPP_year       = \n|HDI                = \n|HDI_year           = }}\n{{Dravidian}}\n{{TNhistory}}\nThe '''Pandya Dynasty,''' also known as the '''Pandyas of Madurai,''' was a dynasty of [[south India]], one of the three ethnically [[List of Tamil monarchs|Tamil lineages]], the other two being the [[Chola dynasty|Chola]] and the [[Chera dynasty|Chera]].<ref name=\":4\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 53\u201354. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref> The rulers of the three dynasties were referred to as \"[[Three Crowned Kings|the three crowned rulers (the mu-ventar)]] of [[Tamilakam|the Tamil country]]\".<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=BbqbAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA57&dq=pandya+dynasty+tamilakam&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5qeq7uILZAhXGWiwKHfKeDh8Q6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=pandya%20dynasty%20tamilakam&f=false|title=Britannica Guide to India|last=Inc|first=Encyclopaedia Britannica|date=2009-03-01|publisher=Encyclopaedia Britannica, Inc.|year=|isbn=9781593398477|location=|pages=57|language=en}}</ref> The Pandyas ruled extensive territories, at times including the large portions of present-day south India and [[Sri Lanka]] (through collateral branches subject to [[Madurai]]).<ref name=\":302\"/><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe age and antiquity of the dynasty is difficult to establish.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Pandya-dynasty|title=Pandya dynasty {{!}} Indian dynasty|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-09-21|language=en}}</ref> The [[Early Pandyan Kingdom|early Pandya]] chieftains<ref name=\":162\">{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Classical Indo-Roman Trade|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2013/26-27/special-articles/classical-indo-roman-trade.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=48|issue=26-27|pages=7\u20138}}</ref> ruled their country [[Pandya Nadu|(the Pandya nadu)]] from time immemorial, which included the inland city of [[Madurai]] and the southern port of [[Korkai]].<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Classical Indo-Roman Trade|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2013/26-27/special-articles/classical-indo-roman-trade.html?0=ip_login_no_cache=3b49b785309ca821ff5e0a285f43e078|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=48|issue=26\u201327}}</ref> The country of the Pandyas finds mention in a number of [[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] sources (as early as 4th century BCE<ref name=\":3\" />) and the edicts [[Maurya dynasty|Maurya]] emperor [[Ashoka|Asoka]] (3rd century BCE).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=lldBAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA401&dq=Ptolemy+pandion&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA6frfnoTZAhWMjywKHT1SAUwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Ptolemy%20pandion&f=false|title=The Periplus of the Erythrean Sea|last=Vincent|first=William|date=1805|publisher=Cadell and Davies|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=403|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":26\"/> The Pandyas are also celebrated in the earliest available Tamil poetry (\"the Sangam literature\").<ref name=\":3\" /> Greek and Latin accounts (early centuries CE), coins with legends in Tamil-Brahmi script, and Tamil-Brahmi inscriptions suggest the continuity of the Pandya dynasty from the 3rd century BCE to early centuries CE.<ref name=\":17\" /> The early historic Pandyas faded into obscurity upon the rise of the [[Kalabhras|Kalabhra dynasty]] in south India.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=327}}\n\nThe Pandyas revived under [[Kadungon]] (r. 590 \u2013 620 CE) towards the end of the 6th century, helped to disestablish the Kalabhras in south India.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} From 6th century to 9th century CE, the [[Chalukyas of Badami]] or [[Rashtrakuta dynasty|Rashtrakutas]] of the Deccan, the [[Pallavas of Kanchi]], and Pandyas of Madurai dominated the politics of south India. The Pandyas, at one time or another, ruled or invaded the fertile estuary of [[Kaveri]] (the Chola country), the ancient [[Chera dynasty|Chera country]] (Kongu and central [[Kerala]]) and [[Venad]]u (south Kerala), the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava country]] and [[Sri Lanka]].{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} The Pandyas went into decline with the rise of the [[Cholas|Cholas of Tanjore]] in the 9th century and were in constant conflict with them. The Pandyas allied themselves with the [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]] (Sri Lanka) and the [[Chera dynasty|Cheras]] in harassing the [[Chola|Chola Empire]] until they found an opportunity for reviving their fortunes during the late 13th century.<ref name=\":252\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 170-72.</ref> The Pandyas were very close allies of the Sinhalese and they often deposited their crowns and other royal insignia with the Sinhalese king for safe-keeping.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sri Lanka and the Cho\u1e37as|author=Wijetunga Mudalige Karunaratna Wijetunga|publisher=Sarvodaya Vishva Lekha Publishers, 2003|page=82}}</ref>\n\nThe Pandyas (1216\u20131345) entered their \"golden age\" under [[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan|Maravarman Sundara I]] and [[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan|Jatavarman Sundara]] I ({{circa|1251}}), who expanded the empire into the Telugu country (as far north as Nellore<ref name=\":3\" />), south Kerala<ref name=\":302\">Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'The Fall of the Old States', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashima, pp. 172\u201373. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref> and conquered [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\":302\"/> The Pandyas of Ucchangi (9th\u201313th century), in the [[Tungabhadra|Tungabhadra Valley]] were related to the Pandyas of Madurai.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDuring their history, the Pandyas were repeatedly in conflict with the [[Pallava]]s, [[Cholas]], [[Hoysalas]], [[Chera dynasty|Cheras (Keralas)]]. An internal crisis in the Pandya empire coincided with the [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] invasion of south India in 1310\u201311.<ref name=\":3\" /> The ensuing political crisis saw more sultanate raids and plunder, the loss of south Kerala (1312), and north Sri Lanka (1323) and the establishment of the [[Madurai Sultanate|Madurai sultanate]] (c. 1334<ref name=\":31\">Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'The Fall of the Old States', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashima, pp. 173\u201374. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>).<ref name=\":10\">Sri Lanka and South-East Asia: Political, Religious and Cultural Relations from A.D. c. 1000 to c. 1500, 1978 By W. M. Sirisena, 57 p.</ref><ref name=\":11\">Politics of Tamil Nationalism in Sri Lanka, South Asian Publishers, 1996 by Ambalavanar Sivarajah, 22 p.</ref> In the mid-16th century, the [[Vijayanagara]] governors of Madurai declared independence and established the [[Madurai Nayak dynasty]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAccording to tradition, the legendary [[Tamil Sangams|Sangams (\"the Academies\")]] were held in [[Madurai]] under the patronage of the Pandyas, and some of the Pandya rulers claim to be poets themselves. The Pandya country was home to a number of renowned temples including [[Meenakshi Temple]] in [[Madurai]]. After the revival of the Pandya power by [[Kadungon]], the Shaivite [[nayanars]] and the Vaishnavite [[alvars]] rose to prominence.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crxUQR_qBXYC&pg=PA68|title=History of People and Their Environs|author=A. Soundaram|publisher=Bharathi Puthakalayam|year=2011|isbn=978-93-80325-91-0|editor1=S. Ganeshram|pages=68\u201369|chapter=The Characteristic Features of Early Medieval Tamil Society|editor2=C. Bhavani}}</ref> It is known that the Pandya rulers followed [[Jainism]] for a short period of time in history.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Etymology and origin legends==\n{{HistoryOfSouthAsia}}\n\nThe word ''pandya'' is thought to be derived from the ancient Tamil word \"pandu\" meaning \"old\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=WTaTDAAAQBAJ&pg=|title=India: The Ancient Past: A History of the Indian Subcontinent from c. 7000 BCE to CE 1200|last=Avari|first=Burjor|date=2016-07-01|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781317236733|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref> The theory suggests that in [[Sangam period|early historic]] Tamil lexicon the word pandya means ''old country'' in contrast with [[Chola]] meaning ''new country'', [[Chera Dynasty|Chera]] meaning ''hill country'' and [[Pallava]] meaning ''branch'' in [[Sanskrit]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=G-87AQAAIAAJ&q=pandyan+longest+rule&dq=pandyan+longest+rule&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZo63Q3IXZAhXGliwKHaekB8YQ6AEIOzAD|title=Journal: Humanities|last=Madras|first=University of|date=1973|language=en}}</ref> The etymology of pandya is still a matter of considerable speculation among scholars. Apart from the derivations mentioned, a number of other theories do appear in historical studies.<ref>{{Cite book|title=On the Original Inhabitants of Bharatavarsa or India|last=Oppert|first=Gustav saloman|publisher=|year=1888|isbn=9925082196|location=|pages=104}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ancient [[Tamil mythology|Tamil legends]], the three brothers ''Cheran'', ''Cholan'' and ''Pandyan'' ruled in common at the southern city of [[Korkai]]. While Pandya remained at home, his two brothers Cheran and Cholan after a separation founded their own kingdoms in north and west.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=zjTneAGmatsC&pg|title=History of Tinnevelly|last=Caldwell|first=Bishop R.|date=1989|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601611|location=|pages=12|language=en}}</ref> Epic poem ''[[Silappatikaram]]'' mentions that the emblem of the Pandyas was that of a ''fish''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=wtYBAAAAMAAJ&q|title=Studies in Ancient Tamil Law and Society|last=N\u0101kac\u0101mi|first=Ir\u0101maccantiran\u0332|date=1978|publisher=Institute of Epigraphy, State Department of Archaeology, Government of Tamilnadu|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=52|language=en}}</ref> The Pandyas assumed several titles, one of them being ''Meenavan'' meaning \"He of the Fish\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=D50ob0i_e0MC&pg|title=Goddesses Who Rule|last=Benard|first=Elisabeth|last2=Moon|first2=Beverly|date=2000-09-21|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=9780195352948|location=|pages=41|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNorth Indian traditions such as the Great Epics and the Puranas often associate southern India with Sage Agastya (who crossed the Vidhyas and travelled south). Agastya appears prominently in medieval Tami literature also.<ref>Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'Beginnings of South Indian History', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 25\u201326. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>\n\nFolklores attributes [[Alli Raani|Alli Rani]] (literally \"the queen Alli\") as one of the [[Sangam period|early historic]] rulers of the Pandyas. She is attributed as a [[Amazons|\"amazonian]] queen\" whose servants were men and administrative officials and army were women.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of the Tamils|last=University|first=Vijaya Ramaswamy, Jawaharlal Nehru|date=2017-08-25|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=|isbn=9781538106860|location=|pages=50|language=en}}</ref> She is thought of ruling the whole western and northern coast of [[Sri Lanka]] from her capital [[Kudiramalai]], where remains of what is thought of as [[Arippu fort|her fort]] are found.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tamil culture in Ceylon: a general introduction|last=Raghavan|first=M. D.|date=1971|publisher=Kalai Nilayam|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=59\u201360|language=en}}</ref> She is sometimes seen as an incarnation of the Pandya associated gods, [[Meenakshi]] and [[Kannaki Amman|Kannagi]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Tamil Temple Myths: Sacrifice and Divine Marriage in the South Indian Saiva Tradition|last=Shulman|first=David Dean|date=2014-07-14|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=|isbn=9781400856923|location=|pages=124|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Pandya kings were said to have belonged to the [[Lunar dynasty|Lunar race]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Madura Country: A Manual|author=James Henry Nelson|publisher=Asian Educational Services, 1989|page=44}}</ref> They claimed [[Pururavas]] and Nahusha as ancestors.<ref>{{cite book|title=Art and Culture of Tamil Nadu|author=Ir\u0101 N\u0101kac\u0101mi, Ir\u0101maccantiran\u0332 N\u0101kac\u0101mi|publisher=Sundeep Prakashan, 1980|page=2}}</ref> Pururavas is listed as one of the ancestors in the [[Velvikudi inscription]] of Nedunchadaiyan Varagunavarman.<ref>{{cite book |author=H. K. Sastri |author-link=H. Krishna Sastri |chapter=Velvikudi Grant of Nedunjadaiyan |title=Epigraphia Indica |volume=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0VwmsGA7ZuoC |year=1983 |publisher=Archaeological Survey of India |ref=harv|page=305 }}</ref> The Sinnamanur plates of Rajasimha III similarly traces his lineage to the Lunar race and also claims that one of his ancestors, a Pandya occupied the seat of [[Indra]] and another Pandyan ancestor forced the ten-headed king of Lanka ([[Ravana]]) to sue for peace.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Sources of Pandya history==\n=== Archaeological sources ===\nPandyas are also mentioned in the inscriptions of [[Maurya dynasty|Maurya]] emperor [[Ashoka|Asoka]] (3rd century BCE). In his inscriptions  (2nd and 13th Major Rock Edict<ref name=\":21\">Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'Beginnings of South Indian History', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 26\u201327. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>)  [[Ashoka|Asoka]] refers to the peoples of south India \u2013 the [[Cholas|Chodas]], [[Chera|Keralaputras]], [[Pandyas]] and [[Satiyaputras]].<ref>Kulke and Rothermund, p104</ref><ref name=\"Keay, p119\">Keay, p119</ref> These polities, although not part of the Maurya empire, were on friendly terms with Asoka:\n\n{{cquote|''The conquest by [[dharma]] has been won here, on the borders, and even six hundred [[yojana]]s (5,400\u20139,600 km) away, where the Greek king [[Antiochus II Theos|Antiochos]] rules, beyond there where the four kings named [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus|Ptolemy]], [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonos]], [[Magas of Cyrene|Magas]] and [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander]] rule, likewise in the south among the [[Cholas]], the Pandyas, and as far as [[Tamraparni]] river.''<ref>[http://www.cs.colostate.edu/~malaiya/ashoka.html S. Dhammika, ''The Edicts of King Ashoka: An English Rendering''] Buddhist Publication Society, Kandy (1994) {{ISBN|955-24-0104-6}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:Mangulam inscription (south India).jpg|thumb|Mangulam inscription (3rd and 2nd centuries BCE)|273x273px|alt=|left]]The earliest Pandya to be found in epigraph is Nedunjeliyan, figuring in the [[Tamil-Brahmi]] [[Mangulam]] inscription (near Madurai) assigned to 3rd and 2nd centuries BCE. The record documents a gift of rock-cut beds, to a [[Jain]] ascetic. It is assumed that the people found in the Mangulam inscription, Nedunjeliyan, Kadalan, and Izhanchadikan predates rulers such as [[Nedunjeliyan II|Talaiyanganam Nedunjelyan]] and Palyaga-salai Mudukudimi Peruvaludi.<ref name=\":18\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 48\u201349. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref><ref name=\":21\" />\n\n[[Kharavela]], the [[Kalinga (historical region)|Kalinga]] king who ruled during c. 1st century BCE, in his [[Hathigumpha inscription]], claims to have destroyed an old confederacy of Tamil countries (\"the tamira\u2013desa\u2013sanghata\") which had lasted 132 years, and to have acquired a large quantity of pearls from the Pandyas.<ref name=\"Keay, p119\" />\n\nSilver [[punch-marked coins]] with the fish symbol of the Pandyas dating from around the same time have also been found.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=IGTaAAAAMAAJ&dq=pandya+punch+coin+bce&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=silver+pandya|title=Trade, ideology, and urbanization: South India 300 BC to AD 1300|last=Champakalakshmi|first=Radha|date=1996|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=123|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Early Tamil literature ===\nThe early historic Pandyas are celebrated in the earliest available [[Sangam literature|Tamil poetry]].<ref name=\":3\" /> The poems refers to about twelve Pandya rulers.<ref name=\":17\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 47\u201348. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref> According to tradition, the legendary [[Tamil Sangams|Sangams (\"the Academies\")]] were held in [[Madurai]] under the patronage of the Pandyas. Several Tamil literary works, such as Iraiyanar Agapporul, mention the legend of three separate Sangams and ascribe their patronage to the Pandyas.<ref name=\"husaini_agapporul\">{{cite book|title=The History of the Pandya Country|last=Husaini|first=Abdul Qadir|page=5}}</ref>\n\nPandya rulers \u2013 such as [[Nedunjeliyan II|Nedunjeliyan]], the Victor of Talaiyalanganam, and Mudukudimi Peruvaludi, the Patron of Several Sacrificial Halls (\"the Palyaga-salai\") \u2013 find mention in a number of poems (such as ''[[Mathuraikkanci]]'').<ref name=\":18\" /><ref name=\":20\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 52\u201353. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>\n\nBeside several short poems found in the ''[[Akananuru]]'' and the ''[[Purananuru]]'' collections, there are two major works \u2013  ''[[Mathuraikkanci]]'' and ''[[Netunalvatai]]'' \u2013  which give a glimpse into the society and commercial activities in the Pandya country during the early historic period.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=2pAMAQAAMAAJ&q=Maduraikkanci&dq=Maduraikkanci&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2mcyd4IXZAhWHhqYKHQNWBAkQ6AEIRDAE|title=A handbook of Tamil Nadu|last=Venkataramaiah|first=K. M.|last2=Linguistics|first2=International School of Dravidian|date=1996|publisher=International School of Dravidian Linguistics|year=|isbn=9788185692203|location=|pages=548|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=5b94AAAAIAAJ&q=Netunalvatai+pandya&dq=Netunalvatai+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq64no4IXZAhWCGCwKHfq3CecQ6AEIOzAD|title=Gleanings from Sangam verses: English version of Sangat Thamizh|last=Karu\u1e47\u0101niti|first=Kalai\u00f1ar Mu|last2=Ara\u1e45kac\u0101mi|first2=Pal\u0332ani|last3=Kal\u0332akam|first3=Ta\u00f1cai Tamil\u0332p Palkalaik|date=1997|publisher=Tamil University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=245|language=en}}</ref> The ''[[Purananuru]]'' and ''[[Agananuru]]'' collections contain poems sung in praise of various Pandya rulers and also poems that were claimed to be composed by the rulers themselves.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nBesides the poems, king Peruvaludi is also mentioned in later copper-plate grant (8th\u20139th century CE).<ref name=\":20\" /> In the work ''[[Mathuraikkanci]]'', the author Mankudi Maruthanar, refers to his patron, [[Nedunjeliyan II|Talaiyanganam Nedunjeliyan]], as the Lord of [[Korkai]] and the Warlord of the Southern [[Parathavar|Parathavar People]].<ref name=\":20\" /> It contains a full-length description of [[Madurai]] and the Pandya country under the rule of Nedunjeliyan. In the famous battle of Talaiyalanganam (in east Tanjore), the Pandya is said to have defeated his enemies (which included the Chera and the Chola).<ref name=\":20\" /> He is also praised for his victory of Mizhalai and Mutturu, two \"vel\" centres along the ocean (in Pudukkottai).<ref name=\":20\" /> The ''[[Nedunalvadai|Netunalvatai]]'' (in the collection of ''[[Pattupattu]]'') by Nakkirar contains a description of king Nedunjeliyan's palace.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=xx7ICQAAQBAJ&pg=PA55&dq=pandyan+purananuru+poem&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2sbDM54XZAhUGiiwKHcrTD0kQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q=pandyan%20purananuru%20poem&f=false|title=Warfare in Pre-British India \u2013 1500BCE to 1740CE|last=Roy|first=Kaushik|date=2015-06-03|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781317586920|location=|pages=55|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign sources ===\nGreek and Latin sources (early centuries CE) refer to the ancient Tamil country, same as the Tamilakam, as \"Lymyrike\" or \"Damirice\" (or Dymirice/Dimirixe or Damirice) and its ruling families.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\n* Pandyas are also mentioned by Greek author [[Megasthenes]] (4th century BCE) where he writes about south Indian kingdom being ruled by women.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=zjTneAGmatsC&pg=PA12&dq=t&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiahoyJ04XZAhXB1SwKHRnEBeAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=History of Tinnevelly|last=Caldwell|first=Bishop R.|date=2004|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601611|location=|pages=16|language=en}}</ref> He described the Pandya country in ''[[Indica (Megasthenes)|Indika]]'' as \"''occupying the portion of India which lies southward and extends to the sea\"''. According to his account, the kingdom had 365 villages, each of which was expected to meet the needs of the royal household for one day in the year. He described the Pandya queen at the time, ''Pandaia'' as the daughter of [[Heracles|Herakles]].<ref name=\"India By John Keay\">India By John Keay</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=zjTneAGmatsC&pg=PA12&dq=t&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiahoyJ04XZAhXB1SwKHRnEBeAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=megasthenes&f=false|title=History of Tinnevelly|last=Caldwell|first=Bishop R.|date=2004|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601611|location=|pages=15|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Pliny the Elder]] refers to the Pandya ruler of Madurai in general terms (first century CE).<ref name=\":17\" />\n* The author of the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'' (first century CE) describes the riches of a \"Pandian kingdom\"<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n{{cquote|...Nelcynda is distant from Muziris by river and sea about five hundred stadia, and is of another kingdom, the Pandian. This place [Nelcynda] also is situated on a river, about one hundred and twenty stadia from the [Arabian] sea.... ''<ref>''Periplus'' 54. Original Greek: \"\u1f29 \u03b4\u1f72 \u039d\u03ad\u03bb\u03ba\u03c5\u03bd\u03b4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b4\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03bc\u1f72\u03bd \u1f00\u03c0\u1f78 \u039c\u03bf\u03c5\u03b6\u03b9\u03c1\u03ad\u03c9\u03c2 \u1f00\u03c0\u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c7\u03b5\u03b4\u1f78\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2, \u1f41\u03bc\u03bf\u03af\u03c9\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03b5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03bf\u1fe6 (\u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u1fc7) \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03b4\u03b9\u1f70 \u03b8\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b4\u03ad \u1f10\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd \u1f11\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2, \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b4\u03af\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\u00b7 \u03ba\u03b5\u1fd6\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b4\u1f72 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u1f74 \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u1f70 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u1f78\u03bd, \u1f61\u03c3\u03b5\u1f76 \u1f00\u03c0\u1f78 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b4\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u1f11\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u03b5\u1f34\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u03b8\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2.\"</ref>}}\n* The country of the Pandyas was described as ''Pandya Mediterranea'' and ''Modura Regia Pandionis'' by [[Ptolemy]] (c. 140 CE<ref name=\":17\" />).<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=Rj5WAAAAYAAJ&q=Ptolemy+pandi+mandala&dq=Ptolemy+pandi+mandala&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwidsd6un4TZAhXB_ywKHbx-Be4Q6AEIXzAH|title=The Cyclopaedia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia|last=Balfur|first=Edward|date=1968|publisher=Akademische Druck- u. Verlagsanstalt|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=105|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Strabo]] states that an Indian king called Pandion sent [[Augustus Caesar]] \"presents and gifts of honour\".<ref name=\":7\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=te1sqTzTxD8C&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72 The First Spring: The Golden Age of India \u2013 Abraham Eraly \u2013 Google Books]. Books.google.co.in. Retrieved on 12 July 2013.</ref><ref name=\":162\"/> The 1st-century [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] historian [[Nicolaus of Damascus]] met, at [[Antioch]], the ambassador sent by a king from India \"named Pandion or, according to others, Porus\" to [[Caesar Augustus]] around 13 CE (Strabo XV.4 and 73).<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0239%3Abook%3D15%3Achapter%3D1%3Asection%3D73 Strabo, Geography, BOOK XV., CHAPTER I., section 73]. Perseus.tufts.edu. Retrieved on 12 July 2013.</ref><ref>Keay, p121</ref>\n* The [[Roman emperor]] [[Julian the Apostate|Julian]] received an embassy from a Pandya about 361 CE.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Chinese historian [[Yu Huan]] in his 3rd-century CE text, the ''Weil\u00fce'', mentions the Panyue kingdom: \n{{cquote|...the kingdom of Panyue is also called ''Hanyuewang''. It is several thousand li to the southeast of [[Tianzhu (India)|Tianzhu]] (northern India)...The inhabitants are small; they are the same height as the Chinese...}} \nScholar John E. Hill identified Panyue as Pandya kingdom.<ref name=\"weilue\">Hill, John</ref> However, others have identified it with an ancient state located in modern [[Burma]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CZQMAQAAMAAJ|title=Between winds and clouds: the making of Yunnan (second century BCE to twentieth century CE)|author=Bin Yang|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-231-14254-0}}</ref> or [[Assam]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dbjLO5l1PCkC&pg=PA12|title=A History of Sino-Indian Relations|author=Yukteshwar Kumar|publisher=APH Publishing|year=2005|isbn=978-81-7648-798-6|page=12}}</ref>\n* The Chinese traveler [[Xuanzang]] mentions a kingdom further south from [[Kanchipuram]], a kingdom named ''Malakutta'', identified with [[Madurai]] described by his Buddhist friends at [[Kanchipuram]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=8XXGhAL1WKcC&pg=PA453&dq=Hiuen+Tsang+malakotta&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivsMHL4oXZAhUG6CwKHdjEBFwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Hiuen%20Tsang%20malakotta&f=false|title=The Early History of India|last=Smith|first=Vincent A.|date=1999|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|year=|isbn=9788171566181|location=|pages=453|language=en}}</ref>\n* In the later part of the 13th century (in 1288 and 1293 CE) [[Venetian Republic|Venetian]] traveller [[Marco Polo]] visited the Pandya kingdom and left a vivid description of the land and its people.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=adpkHQ9SCq0C&pg=PA5 Travel and ethnology in the Renaissance: South India through European eyes, Joan-Pau Rubi\u00e9s]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=11FYACaVySoC&pg=PA9 Muslim identity, print culture, and the Dravidian factor in Tamil Nadu, J. B. Prashant More]</ref>\n{{cquote|The darkest man is here the most highly esteemed and considered better than the others who are not so dark. Let me add that in very truth these people portray and depict their gods and their idols black and their devils white as snow.  For they say that god and all the saints are black and the devils are all white. That is why they portray them as I have described.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-yEfRP0RwgC&pg=PA110 Layers of blackness: colourism in the African diaspora, Deborah Gabriel]</ref>\n}}\n\n== Political history ==\n[[File:An aerial view of Madurai city from atop of Meenakshi Amman temple.jpg|thumb|800px|center|An aerial view of [[Madurai]] city from [[Meenakshi Temple|Meenakshi Amman Temple]] |alt=aerial image of a temple campus]]\n\n===Early Pandyas (c. 3rd century BCE \u2013 c. 3rd century CE)===\n{{Main| Early Pandyan Kingdom}}\n[[File:A_sunrise_over_Vaigai_River_in_Madurai_Tamil_Nadu_India.jpg|alt=|thumb|290x290px|[[Vaigai River]] in Madurai]]\n[[Maurya Empire|Maurya]] emperor [[Ashoka|Asoka]] (3rd century BCE) seems to have been on friendly terms with the people of south India and Sri Lanka (the [[Chola dynasty|Cholas]], the Pandyas, the [[Satiyaputras|Satiya Putras]], the [[Chera dynasty|Kerala Putras]] and the [[Tamraparni]]s). There are no indications that Asoka tried to conquer the extreme south India (the Tamilakam \u2013 the Abode of the Tamils).{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=184}}\n\nThe three chiefly lines of the early historic south India \u2013 the Cheras, Pandyas and Cholas \u2013 were known as the mu-vendar (\"the three vendars\"). They traditionally based at their original headquarters in the interior [[Tamil Nadu]] ([[Karur]], [[Madurai]] and [[Uraiyur]] respectively).<ref name=\":162\"/> The powerful chiefdoms of the three ventar dominated the political and economic life of early historic south India.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=231}} The frequent conflicts between the Chera, the Chola and the Pandya are well documented in ancient (the [[Sangam literature|Sangam]]) Tamil poetry.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=242}} The Cheras, Cholas and Pandyas also controlled the ports of [[Muziris|Muziris (Muchiri)]], [[Korkai]] and Kaveri respectively (for the trade with the [[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] world).<ref name=\":162\"/> The gradual shift from chiefdoms to kingdoms seems to have occurred in the following period.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=231}}[[File:Temple between hill symbols and elephant coin of the Pandyas Sri Lanka 1st century CE.jpg|thumb|Pandya coin with temple between hills and elephant (Sri Lanka -1st century CE) ([[British Museum]]).]]The famous inscription of king [[Kharavela]] at Hathigumpha (mid-first century BCE<ref name=\":162\"/>) mentions the defeat of a confederacy of the \"Tramira\" countries which had been a threat to Kalinga. It also remembers the precious pearls brought to the capital as booty from the \"Pandya\" realm.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=211-212}} The Pandya chiefdom was famous for its pearl fisheries and silk industry.<ref name=\":162\"/> [[Korkai]] and [[Alagankulam]] are believed to have been the exchange centres of the Pandyas. Korkai, a port at the mouth of the river Tambraparni, was linked to the famous pearl fisheries and Alagankulam was also developed as a port.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=229}}\n\nA number of coins attributed to early historic Pandyas are found from the region.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=242}} Inscriptions, datable to c. 2nd century BCE, recording royal grants \u2013 both from royals and wealthy commoners \u2013 were also discovered from the Pandya country.<ref name=\":19\">Thapar, Romila. ''Southern Indian kingdoms'' \"India\". Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. https://www.britannica.com/place/India/The-Shunga-kingdom#ref46870</ref>\n\nThe Pandya seems to be the most prominent of the three \"ventar\" rulers. There are even references to a Pandya queen from 3rd century BCE representing a confederacy of the Tamil countries.<ref name=\":162\"/> [[Madurai]], in south Tamil Nadu, was the most important cultural centre in south India as the core of the Tamil speakers.<ref name=\":19\" /> Megalithic relics such as menhirs, dolmens, urn burials, stone circles and rock-cut chambers/passages can be found in south India. Burial goods include iron objects, ivory ornaments, Black-and-Red Ware and even some [[Roman Empire|Roman Imperial]] coins.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=230}} The so-called \"velir\" hill chieftains are assumed to be associated with these megalithic burials.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=231}}\n\nGreek and Latin accounts (early centuries CE), coins with legends in Tamil-Brahmi script, and Tamil-Brahmi inscriptions suggest the continuity of the Pandya dynasty from the 3rd century BCE to early centuries CE.<ref name=\":17\" /> The early Pandyas, along with the Cheras and the Cholas, were eventually displaced by the [[Kalabhra dynasty]].{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=327}}\n\n''The following is a partial list of Pandya rulers from early historic south India:<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=FjxuAAAAMAAJ&q=A+History+of+South+India+from+the+Early+Times+to+the+Fall+of+Vijayanagar+nilakanta+sastri&dq=A+History+of+South+India+from+the+Early+Times+to+the+Fall+of+Vijayanagar+nilakanta+sastri&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi94vSGs5nZAhVFCiwKHV-nBooQ6AEIKDAA|title=A history of South India from prehistoric times to the fall of Vijayanagar|last=Sastri|first=Kallidaikurichi Aiyah Nilakanta|date=1976|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=22\u201325|language=en}}</ref>'' The early Tami poems mention twelve Pandya rulers.<ref name=\":17\" />\n[[File:S-TN-71 Vettuvan Koil Tuticorin.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Vettuvan Koil|Vettuvan koil]], Kalugumalai, Tuticorin. Pandya kingdom, 8th century CE|alt=]]<blockquote>\n* Koon Pandya\n*[[Nedunjeliyan I]] (\"Aariyap Padai Kadantha\")\n* Puda-pandya\n* \"Palyagasalai\" Mudukudumi Peruvaludi<ref name=\":18\" />\n*[[Nedunjeliyan II]]\n* Nan Maran\n* Nedunj Cheliyan III (\"Talaiyaalanganathu Seruvendra\")<ref name=\":18\" />\n* Maran Valudi\n* Kadalan Valuthi\n* Musiri Mutriya Cheliyan\n* Ukkirap Peruvaludi\n</blockquote>\n\n===Pandya revival (7th\u201310th centuries CE)===\n[[File:FourArmedVishnuPandyaDynasty8-9thCentury.jpg|left|thumb|Enthroned god [[Vishnu]], Pandya dynasty, second half of the 8th\u2013early 9th century CE ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City)]]\n[[File:The Hindu Saint Manikkavacakar LACMA AC1997.16.1 (1 of 12).jpg|thumb|[[Manikkavacakar|Manikkavachakar]], minister of Pandya king Varaguna II (9th century CE) (early 12th century) Los Angeles County Museum of Art]]\n[[File:Double fish Pandyan relief, Koneswaram.jpg|thumb|250px|Jatavarman Veera Pandya II's double fish carp black granite [[Relief|bas-relief]] of the [[Koneswaram temple]] in [[Trincomalee]], reminiscent of the [[Pandya coinage|dynasty's coinage]] symbols found on the island from the [[Pre-modern coinage in Sri Lanka|pre-modern era]], installed after defeating the usurper [[Chandrabhanu]] of [[Tambralinga]]. Pandya affairs in Northern Sri Lanka grew stronger following the intervention of Srimara Srivallabha in 815 CE<ref name=\"Indrapala 2007 324\">{{cite book | last = Indrapala | first = Karthigesu | title = The evolution of an ethnic identity: The Tamils in Sri Lanka C. 300 BCE to C. 1200 CE| publisher = Vijitha Yapa | year = 2007 | page=324|location = Colombo | isbn = 978-955-1266-72-1}}</ref> ]]\nThe Pandya kingdom was revived by king Kadungon (r. 590\u2013620 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}) towards the end of the 6th century CE.<ref name=\":3\" />{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=331}} In the [[Velvikudi inscription]], a later copper-plate, Kadungon appears as the \"destroyer\" of the \"anti-Brahmanical\" [[Kalabhra dynasty|Kalabhra]] kings.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} With the decline of the Kalabhra dynasty, the Pandyas grew steadily in power and territory. With the [[Cholas]] in obscurity in [[Uraiyur]], the Tamil country was divided between the [[Pallavas|Pallavas of Kanchi]] and the Pandyas of Madurai.\n\nFrom 6th century to 9th century CE, the [[Chalukyas of Badami]], the [[Pallavas of Kanchi]], and Pandyas of Madurai dominated the politics of south India. The Badami Chalukyas were eventually replaced by the [[Rashtrakuta dynasty|Rashtrakutas]] in the Deccan.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=84-85}} The Pandyas took on the growing Pallava ambitions in south India, and from time to time they also joined in alliances with the kingdoms of the Deccan Plateau (such as with the [[Western Ganga dynasty|Gangas of Talakad]] in late 8th century CE).<ref name=\":19\" /> In the middle of the 9th century, the Pandyas had managed to advance as far as [[Kumbakonam]] (north-east of Tanjore on the Kollidam river).<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nSendan (r. 654\u201370 CE), the third king of the Pandyas of Madurai, is known for expanding his kingdom to the [[Chera dynasty|Chera country]] (western Tamil Nadu and central [[Kerala]]). Arikesari Maravarman (r. 670\u2013700 CE), the fourth Pandya ruler, is known for his battles against the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallavas of Kanchi]]. Pallava king Narasimhavarman I (r. 630\u201368 CE), the famous conqurer of [[Badami]], claimed to have defeated the Pandyas. [[Chalukya dynasty|Chalukya]] king Paramesvaravarman I \"Vikramaditya\" (r. 670\u2013700 CE) is known to have fought battles with the Pallavas, the Gangas, and probably with the Pandyas too, on the Kaveri basin.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}\n\nKirtivarman II (r. 744/5\u201355 CE), the last Chalukya king, managed to lose to his southern countries as a result of his battles with the Pandyas. Pandya kings Maravarman Rajasimha I (r. 730\u201365 CE) and Nedunjadaiyan/Varagunavarman I (r. 765\u2013815 CE) threatened Pallava king Nandivarman II Pallavamalla (r. 731\u201396 CE) who had managed to defeat the Gangas in around 760 CE. Varagunavarman I invaded the Pallava country, conquered the Kongu country (western Tamil Nadu) and [[Venad]]u (south Kerala). King Srimara Srivallabha (r. 815\u201362 CE) sailed to Sri Lanka, subjugated king Sena I, and sacked his capital [[Anuradhapura]] (the Panya invasion of Sri Lanka followed a period of vassalage).{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} However, Srimara Srivallabha was soon overpowerd by Pallava king Nripatunga (r. 859\u201399 CE). Sena II, the king of Sri Lanka, invaded the Pandya country, sacked Madurai and chose Varagunavarman II (r. c. 862\u2013880 CE<ref name=\":232\"/>) as the new king soon after.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} It is proposed that the start of the [[Malayalam calendar|Kollam Era]], the Kerala calendar, in 825 CE marked the liberation of Venadu from Pandya control.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=89}}\n\nDuring the rule of Dantivarman (r. 796\u2013847 CE), the Pallava territory was reduced by the encroachment from the Pandyas from the south (and Rashtrakutas and the [[Telugu Cholas|Telugu-Chodas]] from north). Pallava king Nandivarman III (r. 846\u201369 CE) was able to defeat the Pandyas and Telugu-Chodas (and even the Rashtrakutas) with the help of the Gangas and the emerging Cholas.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}\n\n''Chronological list of the Pandya kings.''<ref name=\":232\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 165.</ref>\n\n* [[Kadungon]] (r. c. 590\u2013620 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\"/>)\n* Maravarman [[Avani Sulamani|Avanisulamani]] (r. c. 620-645 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* Cheliyan Sendan/Chendan (r. c. 654\u2013670 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Arikesari Maravarman|Arikesari Maravarman (Parankusan)]] (r. c. 670\u2013700 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]] (r. c. 700\u2013730 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Maravarman Rajasimha I]] (r. c. 730\u2013765 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* Parantaka Nedunjadaiyan/Varaguna-varman I{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} (r. c. 765\u2013815 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Srimara Srivallabha|Maravarman Srimara Srivallabha]] (r. c. 815\u2013862 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Varagunavarman II|Varaguna-varman II]] (r. c. 862\u2013880 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* Parantaka Viranarayana (r. c. 880\u2013900/905 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Maravarman Rajasimha III]] (r. c. 900\u2013920 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n\n<br />[[File:Jaina_abode_Kalugumalai.JPG|thumb|600x600px|[[Kalugumalai Jain Beds|Kalugumalai Jain beds]], Pandya kingdom, king Jatila Parantaka Nedunjadayan (8th century CE)|alt=|center]]\n\n===Under Chola influence (10th\u201313th centuries)===\n[[File:South_India_in_12th_century_AD.jpg|thumb|328x328px|Pandya country in the [[Chola dynasty|Chola Empire]] (12th century)]]\nWhile the Pandyas and the Rashtrakutas were busy engaging the Pallavas, with the Gangas and the Simhalas (Sri Lanka) also in the mix, the Cholas emerged from the Kaveri delta and took on the chieftains of [[Thanjavur]]{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=121-123}} (the [[Muthuraja|Mutharaiyar]] chieftain had transferred their loyalty from the Pallava to the Pandya<ref name=\":24\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 167\u201368.</ref>). The [[Chola dynasty|Chola]] king [[Vijayalaya Chola|Vijayalaya]] conquered [[Thanjavur]] by defeating the [[Muthuraja|Mutharaiyar]] chieftain around c. 850 CE.<ref name=\":24\" /> The Pandya control north of the Kaveri river was severely weakened by this move (and straightened the position of the Pallava ruler Nripatunga).<ref name=\":24\" />  Pandya ruler [[Varagunavarman II|Varaguna-varman II]] (r. c. 862\u2013880 CE<ref name=\":232\"/>) responded by marching into the Chola country and facing a formidable alliance of Pallava prince Aparajita, the Chola king Aditya I and the Ganga king Prithvipati I. The Pandya king suffered a crushing defeat (c. 880 CE) in a battle fought near Kumbakonam.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nBy c. 897 CE, Chola king [[Aditya I]] was the master of the old Pallava, Ganga and Kongu countries. It is a possibility that Aditya I conquered the Kongu country from the Pandya king Parantaka Viranarayana (r. 880\u2013900 CE).<ref name=\":24\" /> [[Parantaka I]], successor to Aditya, invaded the Pandya territories in 910 CE and captured Madurai from king Maravarman Rajasimha II (hence the title \"Madurai Konda\").<ref name=\":24\" />  Rajasimha II received help from the Sri Lankan king Kassapa V, still got defeated by [[Parantaka I]] in the battle of Vellur, and fled to Sri Lanka. Rajasimha then found refuge in the Chera country, leaving even his royal insignia in Sri Lanka, the home of his mother.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nThe Cholas were defeated by a Rashtrakuta-lead confederacy in the [[battle of Takkolam]] in 949 CE.<ref name=\":252\"/> By mid-950s, the Chola kingdom had shrunk to the size of a small principality (its vassals in the extreme south had proclaimed their independence).<ref name=\":252\"/> It is a possibility that Pandya ruler Vira Pandya defeated Chola king Gandaraditya and claimed independence.<ref name=\":252\"/> Chola ruler [[Parantaka Chola II|Sundara Parantaka II]] (r. 957\u201373) responded by defeating Vira Pandya in two battles (and Chola prince [[Aditya II]] killed Vira Pandya on the second occasion). The Pandyas were assisted by Sri Lanka forces of king Mahinda IV.<ref name=\":252\"/>\n\nChola emperor [[Rajaraja I]] (r. 985\u20131014 CE) is known to have attacked the Pandyas.<ref name=\":19\" /> He fought against an alliance of the Pandya, [[Chera dynasty|Chera]] and Sri Lankan kings, and defeated the Cheras and \"deprived\" the Pandyas of their ancient capital Madurai.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}} Emperor [[Rajendra Chola I|Rajendra I]] continued to occupy the Pandya kingdom, and even appointed a series of Chola viceroys with the title \"Chola Pandya\" to rule from Madurai (over Pandya and Western Chera/Kerala countries). The very of beginning of Chola emperor [[Kulottunga I|Kulottunga]]'s rule (r. from 1070 CE) was marked by the loss of Sri Lanka and a rebellion in the Pandya country.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}}\n\nThe second half of the 12th century witnessed a major internal crisis in the Pandya country (between princes Parakrama Pandya and Kulasekhara Pandya). The neighbouring kingdoms of Sri Lanka, under [[Parakramabahu I]], [[Venad|Venadu Chera/Kerala]], under the Kulasekharas,{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}} and the Cholas, under [[Rajadhiraja Chola II|Rajadhiraja II]] and [[Kulothunga Chola III|Kulottunga III]], joinined in and took sides with any of the two princes or their kins.<ref>Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 187-90.</ref>{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}}\n\n''The following list gives the names of the Pandya kings who were active during the 10th century and the first half of 11th century.'' <blockquote>\n* Sundara Pandya I\n* Vira Pandya I\n* Vira Pandya II\n* Amarabhujanga Tivrakopa\n* Jatavarman Sundara Chola Pandya\n* Maravarman Vikrama Chola Pandya\n* Maravarman Parakrama Chola Pandya\n* Jatavarman Chola Pandya\n* Srivallabha Manakulachala (1101\u20131124 CE)\n* Maravarman Srivallabha (1132\u20131161 CE)\n*[[Parakrama Pandyan I|Parakrama I]] (1161\u20131162 CE)\n* Kulasekara III\n* Vira Pandya III\n* Jatavarman Srivallabha (1175\u20131180 CE)\n*[[Jatavarman Kulasekaran I|Jatavarman Kulasekara I]] (1190\u20131216 CE)<ref name=\"sen2\">{{Cite book|title=A Textbook of Medieval Indian History|last=Sen|first=Sailendra|publisher=Primus Books|year=2013|isbn=978-9-38060-734-4|pages=45\u201346}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n=== Pandya empire (13th\u201314th centuries) ===\n\nThe Pandya empire included extensive territories, at times including large portions of south India and [[Sri Lanka]]. The Pandya king at Madurai controlled these vast regions through the collateral family branches subject to [[Madurai]].<ref name=\":3\" /> The kingdom was shared among several male royals of the family, one of them enjoying control over the rest.<ref name=\":2\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 208-11.</ref>\n\nThe 13th century saw the rise of seven prime Pandya \"Lord Emperors\" (Ellarkku Nayanar \u2013 Lord of All), who ruled the kingdom alongside other Pandya royals. Their power reached its zenith under [[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan|Jatavarman Sundara I]] in the middle of the 13th century.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA459&dq=maravarman&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE24jHtJnZAhVCCCwKHUbmAuoQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=maravarman&f=false|title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization|last=Sen|first=Sailendra Nath|date=1999|publisher=New Age International|year=|isbn=9788122411980|location=|pages=458|language=en}}</ref>  <blockquote>\n*[[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan|Maravarman Sundara Pandya I]] (1216\u20131238 CE)\n* Sundaravarman Kulasekara II (1238\u20131240 CE)\n*[[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan II|Maravarman Sundara Pandya II]] (1238\u20131251 CE)\n*[[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan|Jatavarman Sundara Pandya I]] (1251\u20131268 CE)\n*[[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Maravarman Kulasekara Pandya I]] (1268\u20131310 CE)\n* Sundara Pandya IV (1309\u20131327 CE)\n* Vira Pandya IV (1309\u20131345 CE)\n</blockquote>The foundation for the Pandya supremacy in south India was laid by [[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan|Maravarman Sundara I]] early in the 13th century.<ref name=\":27\" /> He succeeded his older brother Jatavarman Kulasekhara in 1216.<ref name=\":9\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 203-07.</ref> He invaded the Chola country, sacked [[Uraiyur]] and [[Thanjavur]], and drove the Chola king [[Kulothunga Chola III|Kulothunga III]] into exile.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=XNxiN5tzKOgC&pg=PA411&dq=kulottunga+hoysala+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ0-q015nZAhUFEiwKHVktBXwQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=kulottunga%20hoysala%20pandya&f=false|title=Ancient India|last=Majumdar|first=[[R. C. Majumdar|Ramesh Chandra]]|date=1977|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|year=|isbn=9788120804364|location=|pages=411|language=en}}</ref> The Chola king subsequently made a formal submission to Maravarman Sundara I and acknowledged his overlordship.<ref name=\":9\" /> Attempts by the next Chola king [[Rajaraja Chola III|Rajaraja III]] (1216 \u2013 46 CE<ref name=\":302\"/>) for self-rule (to stop the Pandya invasion into the Chola country<ref name=\":302\"/>), with the help of the [[Hoysala Empire|Hoysalas]] king Narasimha II (r. 1220 \u2013 1238 CE), resulted in a battle between the Pandya and Hoysala forces at Mahendramangalam on the [[Kaveri|Kaveri Valley]]. Maravarman Sundara I was defeated and Rajaraja III was restored in the Chola country.<ref name=\":9\" /> Sometime later Chola prince [[Rajendra Chola III|Rajendra III]] attacked the Pandyas and defeated two Pandya royals including [[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan II|Maravarman Sundara II]].<ref name=\":9\" /> Hoysala king [[Vira Someshwara|Somesvara]] (r. 1233 \u2013 1267 CE<ref name=\":302\"/>) then came to the aid of the Pandyas, defeated Rajendra III and then made peace with the Cholas.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Pandya revival under Jatavarman Sundara Pandya ====\n[[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan I|Jatavarman Sundara I]] ascended the Pandya throne in 1251 CE.<ref name=\":302\"/> He led his army to the Chola country (even as far as [[Nellore]]), to [[Sri Lanka]] and to south [[Kerala]].<ref name=\":302\"/> He was also successful in confining the Hoysala control to the Mysore Plateau (the ancient Chola country was now overrun by the Pandyas<ref name=\":302\"/>).<ref name=\":9\" /> [[Kanchipuram|Kanchi]] functioned as the second major city in the kingdom.<ref name=\":9\" /> In his conquests, Jatavarman Sundara I was assisted by number of Pandya royals such as Jatavarman Vira Pandya.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nJatavarman Sundara I subdued Rajendra III around 1258\u20131260 CE and made him pay tribute.<ref name=\":0\" /> The rule of the Cholas ended c. 1279 with Rajendra III.<ref name=\":302\"/> The Pandya attacked the Hoysalas in the Kaveri and captured the fort of Kannanur Koppam.<ref name=\":9\" /> Hoysala king [[Vira Someshwara|Somesvara]] was forced to fall back into the Mysore Plateau.<ref name=\":9\" /> The Hoysala king, pressed by enemies from north and south, \"assigned\" the southern half of his kingdom to his younger son Ramanatha (r. 1254\u20131292<ref name=\":302\"/>). [[Vira Someshwara|Somesvara]] was eventually killed by the Pandya in 1262 CE.<ref name=\":9\" /> Ramanatha managed to recover Kannanur and hold against the Pandya power.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA459&dq=maravarman&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE24jHtJnZAhVCCCwKHUbmAuoQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=maravarman&f=false|title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization|last=Sen|first=Sailendra Nath|date=1999|publisher=New Age International|year=|isbn=9788122411980|location=|pages=439|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=rB7jAAAAMAAJ&q=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+%22rajendra+III%22&dq=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+%22rajendra+III%22&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVwZuq_ZnZAhVBuSwKHTrDCSIQ6AEIPzAD|title=Proceedings \u2013 Indian History Congress|last=Congress|first=Indian History|date=1957|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=186|language=en}}</ref> Jatavarman Sundara I also came into conflict with the [[Kadava dynasty|Kadava]] ruler [[Kopperunchinga II|Kopperunjinga II]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/delhisultanate00bhar|quote=jatavarman kadava.|title=The History and Culture of the Indian People: The struggle for empire|last=Majumdar|first=Ramesh Chandra|last2=Bhavan|first2=Bharatiya Vidya|date=1966|publisher=Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/delhisultanate00bhar/page/257 257]|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> It seems that Bana (Magadai) and Kongu countries came under the Pandya rule during the wars against the Hoysalas and the Kadavas.<ref name=\":9\" /> Jatavarman Sundara I also fought the Kakatiya ruler Ganapati (1199-1262<ref name=\":302\"/>).<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Sri Lanka]] was invaded by Jatavarman Sundara I in 1258<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=HBQ1AQAAIAAJ&dq=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+chandrabhanu&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+|title=The collapse of the Rajarata civilization in Ceylon and the drift to the south-west: a symposium|last=Intirap\u0101l\u0101|first=K\u0101rttik\u0113cu|date=1971|publisher=Ceylon Studies Seminar, University of Ceylon|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=96|language=en}}</ref> and on his behalf by his younger brother [[Jatavarman Vira Pandyan II|Jatavarman Vira II]] between 1262 and 1264 CE.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=7yULAQAAIAAJ&q=pandya+power+telugu&dq=pandya+power+telugu&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6reCI0ZnZAhXDlCwKHS2SCms4ChDoAQhlMAg|title=Andhra Pradesh District Gazetteers: Prakasam|last=(India)|first=Andhra Pradesh|date=2000|publisher=Director of Print. and Stationery at the Government Secretariat Press; [copies can be from: Government Publication Bureau, Andhra Pradesh]|language=en}}</ref> The island was again invaded and defeated by Jatavarman Vira II in 1270 CE.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=aLYoDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=editions:uCBuXG9qshEC&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwidy9XugZrZAhXMWCwKHRWqBSMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=chandrabhanu&f=false|title=The Hutchinson Dictionary of Ancient and Medieval Warfare|last=Connolly|first=Peter|last2=Gillingham|first2=John|last3=Lazenby|first3=John|date=2016-05-13|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781135936747|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSundara Pandya I (died in 1268) was succeeded by [[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Maravarman Kulasekara I]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Around 1279 the combined force of Hoysala king Ramanatha and [[Rajendra Chola III|Rajendra III]] was defeated by Maravarman Kulasekara I.<ref name=\":2\" /> Maravarman Kulasekara I, now virtually unchallenged, ruled over the Chola country and southern Tamil speaking portions of Hoysala kingdom. He also invaded Sri Lanka, ruled by Bhuvanaikabahu I, \"carried away to the Pandya country the venerable Tooth Relic\", and the wealth of the island.<ref name=\":2\" /> Sri Lanka remained under Pandya control till c. 1308-09 CE.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n====Decline of Pandya empire====\nAfter the death of [[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Maravarman Kulasekhara I]] (1310), his sons Vira Pandya IV and Sundara Pandya IV fought a war of succession for control of the empire. It seems that Maravarman Kulasekhara wanted Vira Pandya to succeed him (who inturn was defeated by Sundara Pandya after a short period of time).<ref>{{cite book|title=Muslim Identity, Print Culture, and the Dravidian Factor in Tamil Nadu|author=J. B. Prashant More|publisher=Orient Blackswan, 2004|page=10}}</ref> Unfortunately, the Pandya civil war coincided with the [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] raids in south India.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sri Varadarajaswami Temple, Kanchi: A Study of Its History, Art and Architecture|author=K.V. Raman|publisher=Abhinav Publications, 2003|page=24}}</ref> Taking advantage of the political situation, the neighbouring [[Hoysala]] king [[Veera Ballala III|Ballala III]] invaded the Pandya territory. However, Ballala had to retreat to his capital, when Khalji general [[Malik Kafur]] invaded his kingdom at the same time.{{sfn|Banarsi Prasad Saksena|1992|p=412}} After subjugating Ballala III, the Khalji forces marched to the Pandya territory in March 1311.{{sfn|Banarsi Prasad Saksena|1992|p=414}} The Pandya brothers fled their headquarters, and the Khaljis pursued them unsuccessfully.{{sfn|Banarsi Prasad Saksena|1992|pp=416\u2013417}}{{sfn|Kishori Saran Lal|1950|pp=208\u2013213}} By late April 1311, the Khaljis gave up their plans to pursue the Pandya princes, and returned to Delhi with the plunder.{{sfn|Kishori Saran Lal|1950|p=212}}{{sfn|Peter Jackson|2003|p=207}} By 1312 the Pandya control over south [[Kerala]] was also lost.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAfter departure of the Khaljis, Vira and Sundara Pandya resumed their conflict. Sundara Pandya was defeated, and sought help from the Khaljis. With their help, he regained control of the [[South Arcot]] region by 1314.{{sfn|Peter Jackson|2003|p=207}} Subsequently, there were two more expeditions from the sultanate in 1314 led by [[Khusro Khan]] and in 1323 by Ulugh Khan ([[Muhammad bin Tughluq]]) under sultan [[Ghiyath al-Din Tughluq]].{{sfn|Peter Jackson|2003|p=207}}\n\nThe family quarrels and the sultanate invasions shattered the Pandya empire beyond revival<ref name=\":3\" /> and coinage discoveries made imply that the Pandyas were left with the old South Arcot region.<ref name=\":12\" /> In 1323, the [[Jaffna Kingdom|Jaffna kingdom]] declared its independence from the crumbling Pandya influence.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" />\n\nWhile the previous sultanate raids were content with plunder, the [[Tughlaq dynasty|Tughluqs]] under Ulugh Khan (later [[Muhammad bin Tughluq]]<ref name=\":31\" />) annexed the former Pandya dominions to the sultanate as the province of Ma'bar. Most of south India came under the sultanate rule and was divided into five provinces \u2013 Devagiri, Tiling, [[Kampili]], [[Halebidu|Dorasamudra]] and Ma'bar.<ref name=\":12\">Nilakanta Sastri, P.213</ref> [[Jalaluddin Ahsan Khan|Jalal ud-Din Hasan Khan]] was appointed governor of the newly created southern-most Ma'bar province.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=uCYdAAAAMAAJ&q=Vira+Someshwara+pandya&dq=Vira+Someshwara+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjpsvuK25nZAhVIEiwKHWYlA7gQ6AEIXzAI|title=Karnataka, History, Administration & Culture|last=Muthanna|first=I. M.|date=1962|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=89|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w6zkx_Ck3FwC&pg=PA171|title=South India and Her Muhammadan Invaders|last=Aiyangar|first=Krishnaswami S.|publisher=Asian Educational Services, 1991 \u2013 India, South|year=1991|isbn=9788120605367|pages=67\u201368,110\u2013111,167,171\u2013174}}</ref> In c. 1334, Jalal ud-Din Hasan Khan declared his independence and created [[Madurai Sultanate|Madurai sultanate]].<ref name=\":31\" /> The Pandyas shifted their capital to [[Tenkasi]] and continued to rule a small area until the end of the 16th century.<ref name=\":31\" />\n\n[[Bukka Raya I]] of [[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagara empire]] conquered the city of Madurai in c. 1370,<ref name=\":31\" /> imprisoned the sultan, released and restored Arcot's prince Sambuva Raya to the throne. Bukka Raya I appointed his son Veera Kumara Kampana as the viceroy of the Tamil region. Meanwhile, Madurai sultanate was replaced by the Nayak governors of [[Vijayanagara]] in 1378.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Comprehensive History of India: Comprehensive history of medieval India|last=Puri|first=B. N.|last2=Das|first2=M. N.|date=2003-12-01|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|year=|isbn=9788120725089|location=|pages=90\u201391|language=en}}</ref> In 1529 the Nayak governors declared independence and established [[Madurai Nayak dynasty]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Economy and society==\n[[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] merchants frequented the [[ancient Tamil country]], present day [[Southern India|south India]] and [[Sri Lanka]], securing contacts with the [[Tamil people|Tamil]] chiefdoms of the Pandya, [[Chola Empire|Chola]] and [[Chera Empire|Chera]] families.<ref name=\":26\" /> The western sailors also established a number of trading settlements on the harbours of the ancient Tamil region.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nThe trade with South Asia by the [[Greco-Roman world]] flourished since the time of the [[Ptolemaic dynasty]]<ref name=\"Lindsay1\">Lindsay (2006) p. 101</ref> a few decades before the start of the [[Common Era]] and remained long after the fall of the [[Western Roman Empire]].<ref name=\"Curtin1\">Curtin 1984: 100</ref><ref name=\"The cyclop\u00e6dia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia\">The cyclop\u00e6dia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia By Edward Balfour</ref> The contacts between south India and the Middle East continued even after the [[Byzantium]]'s loss of the ports of [[Egypt]] and the [[Red Sea]]<ref name=\"Holl1\">Holl 2003: 9</ref> in the 7th century CE.\n\nThe Pandya country, located at the extreme south-western tip of [[South Asia]], served as an important meeting point throughout the history of the India. The location was economically and geopolitically significant as a key point connecting the shipping between [[Southeast Asia]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\n===Coinage===\n{{See also|Pandya coinage}}\n\nThe early coins of [[Tamilakam]] bore the symbols of the [[Three Crowned Kings]], the tiger, the fish and the bow, representing the symbols of the Cholas, Pandyas and Cheras.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=PMVWAAAAMAAJ&dq=pandya+gold+coin&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=pandya+fish+coin|title=Early Indian indigenous coins|last=Sircar|first=Dineshchandra|date=1970|publisher=University of Calcutta|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=98|language=en}}</ref> Coins of Pandyas bear the legend of different Pandya ruler in different times. The Pandyas had [[File:Coin Pandya Bull Obv 2.jpg|thumb|One of the early coins of the Pandyas showing their emblem of the two fishes.]]issued silver [[Punch-marked coins|punch-marked]] and die struck copper coins in the early period.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=9VFmAAAAMAAJ&q=pandya+silver+coin&dq=pandya+silver+coin&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZrt65srXZAhVR3aQKHelDBwcQ6AEIWzAH|title=The Journal of the Numismatic Society of India|last=|first=|date=2005|publisher=Numismatic Society of India|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=67|language=en}}</ref> A few gold coins were attributed to the Pandya rulers of this period. These coins bore the image of fish, singly or in pairs, which where their emblem.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=PMVWAAAAMAAJ&q=pandya+gold+coin&dq=pandya+gold+coin&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic_LK5s7XZAhUP_qQKHbhoC3EQ6AEIbTAJ|title=Early Indian indigenous coins|last=Sircar|first=Dineshchandra|date=1970|publisher=University of Calcutta|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=96|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSome of the coins had the names Sundara, Sundara Pandya or merely the letter 'Su' were etched. Some of the coins bore a boar with the legend of 'Vira-Pandya.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=yyix9TSozmAC&pg=PA49&dq=pandya+coin+sundara&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUuduNtbXZAhVECewKHQpgAosQ6AEINzAC#v=onepage&q=pandya%20coin%20sundara&f=false|title=Dravidian kingdoms and list of Pandiyan coins|last=Savariroyan|first=Pandit D.|date=2004|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120617520|location=|pages=48\u201349|language=en}}</ref> It had been said that those coins were issued by the Pandyas and the feudatories of the Cholas but could not be attributed to any particular king.\n\nThe coins of Pandyas were basically square. Those coins were etched with elephant on one side and the other side remained blank. The inscription on the silver and gold coins during the Pandyas, were in [[Tamil-Brahmi]] and the copper coins bore the Tamil legends.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=JFAaAAAAYAAJ&q=pandya+coin+script&dq=pandya+coin+script&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwir05OctrXZAhWCKewKHQXcCd8Q6AEITjAF|title=Numismatic Studies, Vol|last=Shastri|first=Ajay Mitra|last2=Kumar|first2=Manmohan S.|date=1996-01-01|publisher=Harman Publishing House|year=|isbn=9788185151922|location=|pages=46|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe coins of the Pandyas, which bore the fish symbols, were termed as 'Kodandaraman' and 'Kanchi' Valangum Perumal'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=VjsfAAAAMAAJ&q=Kodandaraman&dq=Kodandaraman&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjY27i-trXZAhUDGuwKHbQpCgcQ6AEIXTAH|title=Tamil Coins: A Study|last=N\u0101kac\u0101mi|first=Ir\u0101maccantiran\u0332|last2=Nagaswamy|first2=R.|date=1981|publisher=Institute of Epigraphy, Tamilnadu State Department of Archaeology|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=102|language=en}}</ref> Apart from these, 'Ellamthalaiyanam' was seen on coins which had the standing king on one side and the fish on the other. 'Samarakolahalam' and 'Bhuvanekaviram' were found on the coins having a [[Garuda]], 'Konerirayan' on coins having a bull and 'Kaliyugaraman' on coins that depict a pair of feet.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=lNx31XT747wC&pg=PA164&dq=pandya+Konerirayan&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbkaSTt7XZAhWB2qQKHSzcB8wQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=pandya%20Konerirayan&f=false|title=South Indian Coins|last=Desikachari|first=T.|date=1991|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601550|location=|pages=164|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Pearl fishing===\n\nThe early historic Pandya country was famous for its supply of pearls. The ancient port of [[Korkai]], in present-day [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]], was the center of pearl trade. Written records from [[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] and Egyptian voyagers give details about the pearl fisheries off the [[Gulf of Mannar]]. [[Megasthenes]] reported about the pearl fisheries, indicating that the Pandyas derived great wealth from the pearl trade.<ref>Kulke and Rothermund, p99, p107</ref>\n\nConvicts were according to the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'' used as pearl divers in [[Korkai]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=PXXsAAAAIAAJ&q=korkai+convicts&dq=korkai+convicts&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAgevMr5nZAhVIjSwKHZ70C9A4ChDoAQgyMAI|title=Tamil social history|last=Subrahmanian|first=N.|last2=Hikosaka|first2=Shu|last3=Samuel|first3=G. John|last4=Thiagarajan|first4=P.|last5=India)|first5=Institute of Asian Studies (Madras|date=1997|publisher=Institute of Asian Studies|language=en}}</ref> The ''Periplus'' even mentions that \"pearls inferior to the Indian sort are exported in great quantity from the marts of Apologas and Omana\".{{sfn|Venkata Subramanian|1988|p=55}}  [[File:Silk route.jpg|thumb|250px| [[Silk Road]] map showing ancient trade routes.]]The pearls from the Pandya country were also in demand in the kingdoms of north India.<ref>{{cite book | last = Iyengar | first = P.T. Srinivasa | title = History of the Tamils: From the Earliest Times to 600 AD | page = 22 | publisher = Asian Educational Services | year = 2001 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ERq-OCn2cloC&pg=PA189&ots=Fp5loyJrzM&dq=musiri+pandyas&sig=aNcEToGTkngMTlXNVQAYgL95TTc#PPA22,M1 | accessdate = 2007-07-15}}</ref> Literary references of the pearl fishing mention how the fishermen, who dive into the sea, avoid attacks from sharks, bring up the right-whorled chank and blow on the sounding shell.<ref>{{cite book | title = A Political and General History of the District of Tinnevelly | last = Caldwell | first = Robert | year = 1881 | page = 20 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ERq-OCn2cloC&pg=PA189&ots=Fp5loyJrzM&dq=musiri+pandyas&sig=aNcEToGTkngMTlXNVQAYgL95TTc#PPA297,M1 | accessdate = 2005-07-15}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nThe Pandya country was home to a number of renowned temples including [[Meenakshi Temple]] in [[Madurai]]. After the revival of the Pandya power by [[Kadungon]], the Shaivite [[nayanars]] and the Vaishnavite [[alvars]] of the Bhakti movement rose to prominence.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIt is known that the Pandya rulers followed [[Jainism]] for a short period of time in history.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Architecture==\n{{further|Pandyan art and architecture}}\n[[File:Tirunelveli Nellaiappar Temple 1.jpg|250px|thumb|upright| The [[Gopuram]] of [[Nellaiappar Temple]] ]]Rock cut and structural temples were a significant part of the Pandya architecture. The [[Vimana (architectural feature)|vimana]] and [[mandapa]] are some of the features of the Pandya temples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=H821AAAAIAAJ&dq=pandyan+architecture&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=vimana|title=Studies in Indian history and culture: volume presented to Dr. P. B. Desai ... on the occasion of his completing sixty years|last=Desai|first=Pandurang Bhimarao|date=1971|publisher=Prof. P. B. Desai Felicitation Committee, Karnatak University; [for copies write to the printer: K. E. B's Print. Press]|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=125|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGroups of small temples are seen at [[Tiruchirappalli district]] of Tamil Nadu. The Shiva temples have a [[Nandi (bull)|Nandi bull]] sculpture in front of the ''maha mandapa''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=TlvqAAAAMAAJ&q=nandi+statue+pandya&dq=nandi+statue+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfwoLPr7XZAhXDzqQKHdiBCWwQ6AEIRDAE|title=Rock-cut temple styles: early Pandya art and the Ellora shrines|last=Rajan|first=K. V. Soundara|date=1998-03-01|publisher=Somaiya Publications|year=|isbn=9788170392187|location=|pages=58|language=en}}</ref> In the later stages of Pandyas rule, finely sculptured idols, [[gopuram]]s on the [[Vimana (architectural feature)|vimanas]] were developed. Gopurams are the rectangular entrance and portals of the temples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=vyXxEX5PQH8C&pg=PA337&dq=gopuram+pandya+temple&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDxcGBsbXZAhWJGuwKHefjApMQ6AEIODAC#v=onepage&q=gopuram%20pandya%20temple&f=false|title=Ornament in Indian Architecture|last=Allen|first=Margaret Prosser|date=1991|publisher=University of Delaware Press|year=|isbn=9780874133998|location=|pages=350|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Meenakshi Amman Temple]] in Madurai and [[Nellaiappar Temple]] in [[Tirunelveli]] were built during the reign of the Pandyas.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=6HAeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA470&dq=meenakshi+temple+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjr0v67sbXZAhVOCewKHVTZA-kQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=meenakshi%20temple%20pandya&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of India|last=Mansingh|first=Surjit|date=2006-05-09|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=|isbn=9780810865020|location=|pages=430|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-1-of-2}}\n* [[Pandyan Civil War (1169\u20131177)]]\n* [[History of Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[History of Kerala]]\n* [[Economy of ancient Tamil country]]\n* [[Industry in ancient Tamil country]]\n{{Col-2-of-2}}\n* [[Tamilakam]]\n* [[Tammuzh]]\n* [[List of Tamil monarchs]]\n* [[Indo-Roman relations]]\n* [[Indo-Roman trade relations]]\n* [[Indian maritime history]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{commons category|Pandyan Dynasty}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Balambal |first=V. |title=Studies in the History of the Sangam Age |date=1998 |publisher=Kalinga Publications |isbn=978-81-85163-87-1 }}\n* Carswell, John. 1991. \"The Port of Mantai, Sri Lanka.\" ''RAI'', pp.&nbsp;197\u2013203.\n* {{cite book |last=Curtin |first=Philip D. |title=Cross-Cultural Trade in World History |year=1984 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-26931-5}}\n* Hill, John E. 2004. ''The Peoples of the West from the Weil\u00fce'' \u9b4f\u7565 ''by Yu Huan'' \u9b5a\u8c62'': A Third Century Chinese Account Composed between 239 and 265 CE.'' [http://depts.washington.edu/silkroad/texts/weilue/weilue.html Draft annotated English translation.]\n* {{cite book |last=Holl |first=Augustin |title=Ethnoarchaeology of Shuwa-Arab Settlements |year=2003 |publisher=Lexington Books |isbn=978-0-7391-0407-1}}\n* {{cite book | last = Husaini| first = A.Q. | title = History of The Pandya Country | year = 1972 }}\n* {{cite book | first= John  | last= Keay | authorlink= | author2= | origyear = 2001| year= 2000| title= India: A history| edition= | publisher= Grove Press | location= India| isbn= 0-8021-3797-0}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Kulke |first1=Hermann |author2=Dietmar Rothermund |title=A History of India |edition=4 |year=2004}}\n* {{cite book  | last = Lindsay  | first = W S  | title = History of Merchant Shipping and Ancient Commerce  | publisher = Adamant Media Corporation  | year = 2006  | isbn = 0-543-94253-8}}\n* {{cite book | first= R | last= Nagasamy| authorlink= | author2= | origyear= | year= 1981| title= Tamil Coins \u2013 A study |edition= | publisher= Institute of Epigraphy, Tamil Nadu State Dept. of Archaeology | location= | id= }}\n* {{cite book | last = Purushottam| first = Vi. Pi. | title = Cankakala Mannar Kalanilai Varalaru | year = 1989}}\n* Ray, Himanshu Prabha, ed. 1996. ''Tradition and Archaeology: Early Maritime Contacts in the Indian Ocean''. Proceedings of the International Seminar Techno-Archaeological Perspectives of Seafaring in the Indian Ocean 4th cent. BC \u2013 15th cent. AD New Delhi, 28 February \u2013 4 March 1994. New Delhi, and Jean-Fran\u00e7ois SALLES, Lyon. First published 1996. Reprinted 1998. Manohar Publishers & Distributors, New Delhi.\n* Reddy, P. Krishna Mohan. 2001. \"Maritime Trade of Early South India: New Archaeological Evidences from Motupalli, Andhra Pradesh.\" ''East and West'' Vol. 51 \u2013 Nos. 1\u20132 (June 2001), pp.&nbsp;143\u2013156.\n* {{cite book | first= Rama Sankar| last= Tripathi| authorlink= | author2= | origyear= | year= 1967| title= History of Ancient India|edition= | publisher= Motilal Banarsidass Publications| location= India| isbn= 81-208-0018-4}}\n* {{cite book | first = K. A. Nilakanta | last = Sastri | origyear = | year= |title = The Pandyan Kingdom: From the Earliest Times to the Sixteenth Century|edition= | publisher= | location= | id= }}\n* {{cite book |first=Lynda |last=Shaffer |title=Maritime Southeast Asia to 1500 (Sources and Studies in World History) |publisher=M.E. Sharpe |location=Armonk, N.Y |year=1996 |pages= |isbn=1-56324-144-7 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}\n* {{cite book |author=N. Subrahmanian |title=History of Tamilnad (To A. D. 1336) |url=http://www.dli.ernet.in/handle/2015/462306 |year=1962 |publisher=Koodal |location=Madurai |oclc=43502446 |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20161123181101/http://www.dli.ernet.in/handle/2015/462306 |archivedate=23 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }}\n* {{cite book|last=Venkata Subramanian |first=T. K. |title=Environment and Urbanisation in Early Tamilakam |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NN4fAAAAIAAJ |page=55 |date=1988 |publisher=Tamil University |isbn=978-81-7090-110-5 |work=Issue 92 of Tamil_p Palkalaik Kal_aka ve?iyi?u |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |author=Banarsi Prasad Saksena |author-link=Banarsi Prasad Saksena |chapter=The Khaljis: Alauddin Khalji |editor=Mohammad Habib and Khaliq Ahmad Nizami |title=A Comprehensive History of India: The Delhi Sultanat (A.D. 1206\u20131526) |volume=5 |edition=Second |year=1992 |publisher=The Indian History Congress / People's Publishing House |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_9cmAQAAMAAJ |oclc=31870180 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite journal |author=K.K.R. Nair |title=Venad: Its Early History |journal=Journal of Kerala Studies |volume=14 |issue=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EgSSAAAAIAAJ |year=1987 |publisher=University of Kerala |issn=0377-0443 |pages=1\u201334 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |author=Kishori Saran Lal |author-link=K. S. Lal |title=History of the Khaljis (1290\u20131320) |year=1950 |publisher=The Indian Press |location=Allahabad |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2XXqAQAACAAJ |oclc=685167335 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |editor=Noboru Karashima |title=A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fpdVoAEACAAJ |year=2014 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-809977-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |author=Romila Thapar |title=The Penguin History of Early India: From the Origins to AD 1300 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gyiqZKDlSBMC |year=2003 |publisher=Penguin Books India |isbn=978-0-14-302989-2 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |author=Peter Jackson |author-link=Peter Jackson (historian) |title=The Delhi Sultanate: A Political and Military History |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lt2tqOpVRKgC&pg=PA174 |year=2003 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-54329-3 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Tribes and kingdoms of the Mahabharata}}\n{{Middle kingdoms of India}}\n{{Jaffna kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Tamil history]]\n[[Category:Pandyan dynasty| ]]\n[[Category:Empires and kingdoms of India]]\n[[Category:Tamil monarchs]]\n[[Category:Tirunelveli]]\n[[Category:History of Tiruchirappalli]]\n[[Category:1st-millennium BC establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect| Pandya|the surname| Pande}}\n{{short description|Ancient Tamil dynasty}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|conventional_long_name = Pandya Empire\n|common_name        = Pandya Empire\n|era                = \n|year_start         = \n|year_end           = \n|p1                 = \n|p2                 = \n|s1                 = Delhi Sultanate\n|s2                 = Madurai Nayak dynasty\n|s3                 = Jaffna kingdom\n|s4                 = Sambuvaraya\n|image_map          = Pandya Kingdom (south India).png\n|image_map_caption  = Pandya Empire (12th\u201314th century CE)\n|official_languages = \n*[[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n*[[Sanskrit]]<ref>{{cite book |author=Upinder Singh |title=A History of Ancient and Early Medieval India: From the Stone Age to the 12th Century |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H3lUIIYxWkEC&pg=PA46 |year=2008 |publisher=Pearson Education India |isbn=978-81-317-1120-0 |page=46 |quote=Kings of the Chola and Pandya dynasties also issued Tamil and bilingual Sanskrit\u2013Tamil inscriptions. }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=C. Sivaramamurti |title=L'Art en Inde |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WKgQAQAAMAAJ |year=1977|publisher=H. N. Abrams |isbn=978-0-8109-0630-3 |p=60 |quote=Thus the state language was Sanskrit whether the inscriptions were from the north or the south and whether the dynasty was Gupta, Vakatak[a], Vardhana, Maukhari, Pratihara, Paramara, Chandella, Pala, Sena, Gahadavala, Haihaya, Ganga, Pallava, Chola, Pandya, Chalukya, Rashtrakuta, or Vijayanagar[a]. Inscriptions were sometimes written in regional languages, but they invariably had a preface in Sanskrit. }}</ref>\n|capital            = \n*[[Madurai]] (till mid-14th century)<ref name=\":31\" />\n*[[Korkai]] (port, early historic)<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Classical Indo-Roman Trade|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2013/26-27/special-articles/classical-indo-roman-trade.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=48|issue=26\u201327}}</ref>\n*[[Tenkasi]] (mid-14th century\u2013end of the 16th century CE)<ref name=\":31\" />\n|religion           = [[Hinduism]]<br>[[Jainism]]\n|government_type    = Monarchy\n|leader1            = [[Kadungon]]\n|year_leader1       = 560\u2013590 CE\n|leader2            = \"Five Pandyas\"\n|year_leader2       = 1100\u20131400 CE\n|today              = [[India]]<br />[[Sri Lanka]]\n|demonym            = \n|area_km2           = \n|area_rank          = \n|GDP_PPP            = \n|GDP_PPP_year       = \n|HDI                = \n|HDI_year           = }}\n{{Dravidian}}\n{{TNhistory}}\nThe '''Pandya Dynasty,''' also known as the '''Pandyas of Madurai,''' was a dynasty of [[south India]], one of the three ethnically [[List of Tamil monarchs|Tamil lineages]], the other two being the [[Chola dynasty|Chola]] and the [[Chera dynasty|Chera]].<ref name=\":4\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 53\u201354. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref> The rulers of the three dynasties were referred to as \"[[Three Crowned Kings|the three crowned rulers (the mu-ventar)]] of [[Tamilakam|the Tamil country]]\".<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=BbqbAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA57&dq=pandya+dynasty+tamilakam&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5qeq7uILZAhXGWiwKHfKeDh8Q6AEILzAB#v=onepage&q=pandya%20dynasty%20tamilakam&f=false|title=Britannica Guide to India|last=Inc|first=Encyclopaedia Britannica|date=2009-03-01|publisher=Encyclopaedia Britannica, Inc.|year=|isbn=9781593398477|location=|pages=57|language=en}}</ref> The Pandyas ruled extensive territories, at times including the large portions of present-day south India and [[Sri Lanka]] (through collateral branches subject to [[Madurai]]).<ref name=\":302\"/><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe age and antiquity of the dynasty is difficult to establish.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Pandya-dynasty|title=Pandya dynasty {{!}} Indian dynasty|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=2017-09-21|language=en}}</ref> The [[Early Pandyan Kingdom|early Pandya]] chieftains<ref name=\":162\">{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Classical Indo-Roman Trade|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2013/26-27/special-articles/classical-indo-roman-trade.html|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=48|issue=26-27|pages=7\u20138}}</ref> ruled their country [[Pandya Nadu|(the Pandya nadu)]] from time immemorial, which included the inland city of [[Madurai]] and the southern port of [[Korkai]].<ref name=\":26\">{{Cite journal|date=2015-06-05|title=Classical Indo-Roman Trade|url=https://www.epw.in/journal/2013/26-27/special-articles/classical-indo-roman-trade.html?0=ip_login_no_cache=3b49b785309ca821ff5e0a285f43e078|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|language=en|volume=48|issue=26\u201327}}</ref> The country of the Pandyas finds mention in a number of [[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] sources (as early as 4th century BCE<ref name=\":3\" />) and the edicts [[Maurya dynasty|Maurya]] emperor [[Ashoka|Asoka]] (3rd century BCE).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=lldBAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA401&dq=Ptolemy+pandion&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA6frfnoTZAhWMjywKHT1SAUwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Ptolemy%20pandion&f=false|title=The Periplus of the Erythrean Sea|last=Vincent|first=William|date=1805|publisher=Cadell and Davies|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=403|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":26\"/> The Pandyas are also celebrated in the earliest available Tamil poetry (\"the Sangam literature\").<ref name=\":3\" /> Greek and Latin accounts (early centuries CE), coins with legends in Tamil-Brahmi script, and Tamil-Brahmi inscriptions suggest the continuity of the Pandya dynasty from the 3rd century BCE to early centuries CE.<ref name=\":17\" /> The early historic Pandyas faded into obscurity upon the rise of the [[Kalabhras|Kalabhra dynasty]] in south India.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=327}}\n\nThe Pandyas revived under [[Kadungon]] (r. 590 \u2013 620 CE) towards the end of the 6th century, helped to disestablish the Kalabhras in south India.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} From 6th century to 9th century CE, the [[Chalukyas of Badami]] or [[Rashtrakuta dynasty|Rashtrakutas]] of the Deccan, the [[Pallavas of Kanchi]], and Pandyas of Madurai dominated the politics of south India. The Pandyas, at one time or another, ruled or invaded the fertile estuary of [[Kaveri]] (the Chola country), the ancient [[Chera dynasty|Chera country]] (Kongu and central [[Kerala]]) and [[Venad]]u (south Kerala), the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallava country]] and [[Sri Lanka]].{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} The Pandyas went into decline with the rise of the [[Cholas|Cholas of Tanjore]] in the 9th century and were in constant conflict with them. The Pandyas allied themselves with the [[Sinhalese]] (Sri Lanka) and the [[Chera dynasty|Cheras]] in harassing the [[Chola|Chola Empire]] until they found an opportunity for reviving their fortunes during the late 13th century.<ref name=\":252\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 170-72.</ref> The Pandyas were very close allies of the Sinhalese and they often deposited their crowns and other royal insignia with the Sinhalese king for safe-keeping.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sri Lanka and the Cho\u1e37as|author=Wijetunga Mudalige Karunaratna Wijetunga|publisher=Sarvodaya Vishva Lekha Publishers, 2003|page=82}}</ref>\n\nThe Pandyas (1216\u20131345) entered their \"golden age\" under [[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan|Maravarman Sundara I]] and [[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan|Jatavarman Sundara]] I ({{circa|1251}}), who expanded the empire into the Telugu country (as far north as Nellore<ref name=\":3\" />), south Kerala<ref name=\":302\">Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'The Fall of the Old States', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashima, pp. 172\u201373. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref> and conquered [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=\":302\"/> The Pandyas of Ucchangi (9th\u201313th century), in the [[Tungabhadra|Tungabhadra Valley]] were related to the Pandyas of Madurai.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDuring their history, the Pandyas were repeatedly in conflict with the [[Pallava]]s, [[Cholas]], [[Hoysalas]], [[Chera dynasty|Cheras (Keralas)]]. An internal crisis in the Pandya empire coincided with the [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] invasion of south India in 1310\u201311.<ref name=\":3\" /> The ensuing political crisis saw more sultanate raids and plunder, the loss of south Kerala (1312), and north Sri Lanka (1323) and the establishment of the [[Madurai Sultanate|Madurai sultanate]] (c. 1334<ref name=\":31\">Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'The Fall of the Old States', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashima, pp. 173\u201374. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>).<ref name=\":10\">Sri Lanka and South-East Asia: Political, Religious and Cultural Relations from A.D. c. 1000 to c. 1500, 1978 By W. M. Sirisena, 57 p.</ref><ref name=\":11\">Politics of Tamil Nationalism in Sri Lanka, South Asian Publishers, 1996 by Ambalavanar Sivarajah, 22 p.</ref> In the mid-16th century, the [[Vijayanagara]] governors of Madurai declared independence and established the [[Madurai Nayak dynasty]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAccording to tradition, the legendary [[Tamil Sangams|Sangams (\"the Academies\")]] were held in [[Madurai]] under the patronage of the Pandyas, and some of the Pandya rulers claim to be poets themselves. The Pandya country was home to a number of renowned temples including [[Meenakshi Temple]] in [[Madurai]]. After the revival of the Pandya power by [[Kadungon]], the Shaivite [[nayanars]] and the Vaishnavite [[alvars]] rose to prominence.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crxUQR_qBXYC&pg=PA68|title=History of People and Their Environs|author=A. Soundaram|publisher=Bharathi Puthakalayam|year=2011|isbn=978-93-80325-91-0|editor1=S. Ganeshram|pages=68\u201369|chapter=The Characteristic Features of Early Medieval Tamil Society|editor2=C. Bhavani}}</ref> It is known that the Pandya rulers followed [[Jainism]] for a short period of time in history.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Etymology and origin legends==\n{{HistoryOfSouthAsia}}\n\nThe word ''pandya'' is thought to be derived from the ancient Tamil word \"pandu\" meaning \"old\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=WTaTDAAAQBAJ&pg=|title=India: The Ancient Past: A History of the Indian Subcontinent from c. 7000 BCE to CE 1200|last=Avari|first=Burjor|date=2016-07-01|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781317236733|location=|pages=249|language=en}}</ref> The theory suggests that in [[Sangam period|early historic]] Tamil lexicon the word pandya means ''old country'' in contrast with [[Chola]] meaning ''new country'', [[Chera Dynasty|Chera]] meaning ''hill country'' and [[Pallava]] meaning ''branch'' in [[Sanskrit]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=G-87AQAAIAAJ&q=pandyan+longest+rule&dq=pandyan+longest+rule&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZo63Q3IXZAhXGliwKHaekB8YQ6AEIOzAD|title=Journal: Humanities|last=Madras|first=University of|date=1973|language=en}}</ref> The etymology of pandya is still a matter of considerable speculation among scholars. Apart from the derivations mentioned, a number of other theories do appear in historical studies.<ref>{{Cite book|title=On the Original Inhabitants of Bharatavarsa or India|last=Oppert|first=Gustav saloman|publisher=|year=1888|isbn=9925082196|location=|pages=104}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ancient [[Tamil mythology|Tamil legends]], the three brothers ''Cheran'', ''Cholan'' and ''Pandyan'' ruled in common at the southern city of [[Korkai]]. While Pandya remained at home, his two brothers Cheran and Cholan after a separation founded their own kingdoms in north and west.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=zjTneAGmatsC&pg|title=History of Tinnevelly|last=Caldwell|first=Bishop R.|date=1989|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601611|location=|pages=12|language=en}}</ref> Epic poem ''[[Silappatikaram]]'' mentions that the emblem of the Pandyas was that of a ''fish''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=wtYBAAAAMAAJ&q|title=Studies in Ancient Tamil Law and Society|last=N\u0101kac\u0101mi|first=Ir\u0101maccantiran\u0332|date=1978|publisher=Institute of Epigraphy, State Department of Archaeology, Government of Tamilnadu|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=52|language=en}}</ref> The Pandyas assumed several titles, one of them being ''Meenavan'' meaning \"He of the Fish\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=D50ob0i_e0MC&pg|title=Goddesses Who Rule|last=Benard|first=Elisabeth|last2=Moon|first2=Beverly|date=2000-09-21|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=9780195352948|location=|pages=41|language=en}}</ref>\n\nNorth Indian traditions such as the Great Epics and the Puranas often associate southern India with Sage Agastya (who crossed the Vidhyas and travelled south). Agastya appears prominently in medieval Tami literature also.<ref>Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'Beginnings of South Indian History', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 25\u201326. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>\n\nFolklores attributes [[Alli Raani|Alli Rani]] (literally \"the queen Alli\") as one of the [[Sangam period|early historic]] rulers of the Pandyas. She is attributed as a [[Amazons|\"amazonian]] queen\" whose servants were men and administrative officials and army were women.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Historical Dictionary of the Tamils|last=University|first=Vijaya Ramaswamy, Jawaharlal Nehru|date=2017-08-25|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=|isbn=9781538106860|location=|pages=50|language=en}}</ref> She is thought of ruling the whole western and northern coast of [[Sri Lanka]] from her capital [[Kudiramalai]], where remains of what is thought of as [[Arippu fort|her fort]] are found.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Tamil culture in Ceylon: a general introduction|last=Raghavan|first=M. D.|date=1971|publisher=Kalai Nilayam|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=59\u201360|language=en}}</ref> She is sometimes seen as an incarnation of the Pandya associated gods, [[Meenakshi]] and [[Kannaki Amman|Kannagi]].<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Tamil Temple Myths: Sacrifice and Divine Marriage in the South Indian Saiva Tradition|last=Shulman|first=David Dean|date=2014-07-14|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=|isbn=9781400856923|location=|pages=124|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Pandya kings were said to have belonged to the [[Lunar dynasty|Lunar race]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Madura Country: A Manual|author=James Henry Nelson|publisher=Asian Educational Services, 1989|page=44}}</ref> They claimed [[Pururavas]] and Nahusha as ancestors.<ref>{{cite book|title=Art and Culture of Tamil Nadu|author=Ir\u0101 N\u0101kac\u0101mi, Ir\u0101maccantiran\u0332 N\u0101kac\u0101mi|publisher=Sundeep Prakashan, 1980|page=2}}</ref> Pururavas is listed as one of the ancestors in the [[Velvikudi inscription]] of Nedunchadaiyan Varagunavarman.<ref>{{cite book |author=H. K. Sastri |author-link=H. Krishna Sastri |chapter=Velvikudi Grant of Nedunjadaiyan |title=Epigraphia Indica |volume=17 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0VwmsGA7ZuoC |year=1983 |publisher=Archaeological Survey of India |ref=harv|page=305 }}</ref> The Sinnamanur plates of Rajasimha III similarly traces his lineage to the Lunar race and also claims that one of his ancestors, a Pandya occupied the seat of [[Indra]] and another Pandyan ancestor forced the ten-headed king of Lanka ([[Ravana]]) to sue for peace.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Sources of Pandya history==\n=== Archaeological sources ===\nPandyas are also mentioned in the inscriptions of [[Maurya dynasty|Maurya]] emperor [[Ashoka|Asoka]] (3rd century BCE). In his inscriptions  (2nd and 13th Major Rock Edict<ref name=\":21\">Karashima, Noburu. 2014. 'Beginnings of South Indian History', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 26\u201327. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>)  [[Ashoka|Asoka]] refers to the peoples of south India \u2013 the [[Cholas|Chodas]], [[Chera|Keralaputras]], [[Pandyas]] and [[Satiyaputras]].<ref>Kulke and Rothermund, p104</ref><ref name=\"Keay, p119\">Keay, p119</ref> These polities, although not part of the Maurya empire, were on friendly terms with Asoka:\n\n{{cquote|''The conquest by [[dharma]] has been won here, on the borders, and even six hundred [[yojana]]s (5,400\u20139,600 km) away, where the Greek king [[Antiochus II Theos|Antiochos]] rules, beyond there where the four kings named [[Ptolemy II Philadelphus|Ptolemy]], [[Antigonus II Gonatas|Antigonos]], [[Magas of Cyrene|Magas]] and [[Alexander II of Epirus|Alexander]] rule, likewise in the south among the [[Cholas]], the Pandyas, and as far as [[Tamraparni]] river.''<ref>[http://www.cs.colostate.edu/~malaiya/ashoka.html S. Dhammika, ''The Edicts of King Ashoka: An English Rendering''] Buddhist Publication Society, Kandy (1994) {{ISBN|955-24-0104-6}}</ref>\n}}\n\n[[File:Mangulam inscription (south India).jpg|thumb|Mangulam inscription (3rd and 2nd centuries BCE)|273x273px|alt=|left]]The earliest Pandya to be found in epigraph is Nedunjeliyan, figuring in the [[Tamil-Brahmi]] [[Mangulam]] inscription (near Madurai) assigned to 3rd and 2nd centuries BCE. The record documents a gift of rock-cut beds, to a [[Jain]] ascetic. It is assumed that the people found in the Mangulam inscription, Nedunjeliyan, Kadalan, and Izhanchadikan predates rulers such as [[Nedunjeliyan II|Talaiyanganam Nedunjelyan]] and Palyaga-salai Mudukudimi Peruvaludi.<ref name=\":18\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 48\u201349. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref><ref name=\":21\" />\n\n[[Kharavela]], the [[Kalinga (historical region)|Kalinga]] king who ruled during c. 1st century BCE, in his [[Hathigumpha inscription]], claims to have destroyed an old confederacy of Tamil countries (\"the tamira\u2013desa\u2013sanghata\") which had lasted 132 years, and to have acquired a large quantity of pearls from the Pandyas.<ref name=\"Keay, p119\" />\n\nSilver [[punch-marked coins]] with the fish symbol of the Pandyas dating from around the same time have also been found.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=IGTaAAAAMAAJ&dq=pandya+punch+coin+bce&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=silver+pandya|title=Trade, ideology, and urbanization: South India 300 BC to AD 1300|last=Champakalakshmi|first=Radha|date=1996|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=123|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Early Tamil literature ===\nThe early historic Pandyas are celebrated in the earliest available [[Sangam literature|Tamil poetry]].<ref name=\":3\" /> The poems refers to about twelve Pandya rulers.<ref name=\":17\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 47\u201348. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref> According to tradition, the legendary [[Tamil Sangams|Sangams (\"the Academies\")]] were held in [[Madurai]] under the patronage of the Pandyas. Several Tamil literary works, such as Iraiyanar Agapporul, mention the legend of three separate Sangams and ascribe their patronage to the Pandyas.<ref name=\"husaini_agapporul\">{{cite book|title=The History of the Pandya Country|last=Husaini|first=Abdul Qadir|page=5}}</ref>\n\nPandya rulers \u2013 such as [[Nedunjeliyan II|Nedunjeliyan]], the Victor of Talaiyalanganam, and Mudukudimi Peruvaludi, the Patron of Several Sacrificial Halls (\"the Palyaga-salai\") \u2013 find mention in a number of poems (such as ''[[Mathuraikkanci]]'').<ref name=\":18\" /><ref name=\":20\">Subbarayalu, Y. 2014. 'Early Tamil Polity', in ''A Concise History of South India: Issues and Interpretations'', ed. Noburu Karashmia, pp. 52\u201353. New Delhi: Oxford University Press.</ref>\n\nBeside several short poems found in the ''[[Akananuru]]'' and the ''[[Purananuru]]'' collections, there are two major works \u2013  ''[[Mathuraikkanci]]'' and ''[[Netunalvatai]]'' \u2013  which give a glimpse into the society and commercial activities in the Pandya country during the early historic period.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=2pAMAQAAMAAJ&q=Maduraikkanci&dq=Maduraikkanci&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2mcyd4IXZAhWHhqYKHQNWBAkQ6AEIRDAE|title=A handbook of Tamil Nadu|last=Venkataramaiah|first=K. M.|last2=Linguistics|first2=International School of Dravidian|date=1996|publisher=International School of Dravidian Linguistics|year=|isbn=9788185692203|location=|pages=548|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=5b94AAAAIAAJ&q=Netunalvatai+pandya&dq=Netunalvatai+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjq64no4IXZAhWCGCwKHfq3CecQ6AEIOzAD|title=Gleanings from Sangam verses: English version of Sangat Thamizh|last=Karu\u1e47\u0101niti|first=Kalai\u00f1ar Mu|last2=Ara\u1e45kac\u0101mi|first2=Pal\u0332ani|last3=Kal\u0332akam|first3=Ta\u00f1cai Tamil\u0332p Palkalaik|date=1997|publisher=Tamil University|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=245|language=en}}</ref> The ''[[Purananuru]]'' and ''[[Agananuru]]'' collections contain poems sung in praise of various Pandya rulers and also poems that were claimed to be composed by the rulers themselves.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nBesides the poems, king Peruvaludi is also mentioned in later copper-plate grant (8th\u20139th century CE).<ref name=\":20\" /> In the work ''[[Mathuraikkanci]]'', the author Mankudi Maruthanar, refers to his patron, [[Nedunjeliyan II|Talaiyanganam Nedunjeliyan]], as the Lord of [[Korkai]] and the Warlord of the Southern [[Parathavar|Parathavar People]].<ref name=\":20\" /> It contains a full-length description of [[Madurai]] and the Pandya country under the rule of Nedunjeliyan. In the famous battle of Talaiyalanganam (in east Tanjore), the Pandya is said to have defeated his enemies (which included the Chera and the Chola).<ref name=\":20\" /> He is also praised for his victory of Mizhalai and Mutturu, two \"vel\" centres along the ocean (in Pudukkottai).<ref name=\":20\" /> The ''[[Nedunalvadai|Netunalvatai]]'' (in the collection of ''[[Pattupattu]]'') by Nakkirar contains a description of king Nedunjeliyan's palace.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=xx7ICQAAQBAJ&pg=PA55&dq=pandyan+purananuru+poem&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi2sbDM54XZAhUGiiwKHcrTD0kQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q=pandyan%20purananuru%20poem&f=false|title=Warfare in Pre-British India \u2013 1500BCE to 1740CE|last=Roy|first=Kaushik|date=2015-06-03|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781317586920|location=|pages=55|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Foreign sources ===\nGreek and Latin sources (early centuries CE) refer to the ancient Tamil country, same as the Tamilakam, as \"Lymyrike\" or \"Damirice\" (or Dymirice/Dimirixe or Damirice) and its ruling families.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\n* Pandyas are also mentioned by Greek author [[Megasthenes]] (4th century BCE) where he writes about south Indian kingdom being ruled by women.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=zjTneAGmatsC&pg=PA12&dq=t&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiahoyJ04XZAhXB1SwKHRnEBeAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=History of Tinnevelly|last=Caldwell|first=Bishop R.|date=2004|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601611|location=|pages=16|language=en}}</ref> He described the Pandya country in ''[[Indica (Megasthenes)|Indika]]'' as \"''occupying the portion of India which lies southward and extends to the sea\"''. According to his account, the kingdom had 365 villages, each of which was expected to meet the needs of the royal household for one day in the year. He described the Pandya queen at the time, ''Pandaia'' as the daughter of [[Heracles|Herakles]].<ref name=\"India By John Keay\">India By John Keay</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=zjTneAGmatsC&pg=PA12&dq=t&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiahoyJ04XZAhXB1SwKHRnEBeAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=megasthenes&f=false|title=History of Tinnevelly|last=Caldwell|first=Bishop R.|date=2004|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601611|location=|pages=15|language=en}}</ref>\n*[[Pliny the Elder]] refers to the Pandya ruler of Madurai in general terms (first century CE).<ref name=\":17\" />\n* The author of the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'' (first century CE) describes the riches of a \"Pandian kingdom\"<ref name=\":17\" /><ref name=\":6\" />\n{{cquote|...Nelcynda is distant from Muziris by river and sea about five hundred stadia, and is of another kingdom, the Pandian. This place [Nelcynda] also is situated on a river, about one hundred and twenty stadia from the [Arabian] sea.... ''<ref>''Periplus'' 54. Original Greek: \"\u1f29 \u03b4\u1f72 \u039d\u03ad\u03bb\u03ba\u03c5\u03bd\u03b4\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b4\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u03bc\u1f72\u03bd \u1f00\u03c0\u1f78 \u039c\u03bf\u03c5\u03b6\u03b9\u03c1\u03ad\u03c9\u03c2 \u1f00\u03c0\u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c7\u03b5\u03b4\u1f78\u03bd \u03c0\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03af\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2, \u1f41\u03bc\u03bf\u03af\u03c9\u03c2 \u03b4\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03b5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03bf\u1fe6 (\u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u1fc7) \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03b4\u03b9\u1f70 \u03b8\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03b9\u03bb\u03b5\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03b4\u03ad \u1f10\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03bd \u1f11\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2, \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b4\u03af\u03bf\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2\u00b7 \u03ba\u03b5\u1fd6\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 \u03b4\u1f72 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u1f74 \u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u1f70 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u1f78\u03bd, \u1f61\u03c3\u03b5\u1f76 \u1f00\u03c0\u1f78 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03b4\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u1f11\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u03b5\u1f34\u03ba\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9 \u03c4\u1fc6\u03c2 \u03b8\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2.\"</ref>}}\n* The country of the Pandyas was described as ''Pandya Mediterranea'' and ''Modura Regia Pandionis'' by [[Ptolemy]] (c. 140 CE<ref name=\":17\" />).<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=Rj5WAAAAYAAJ&q=Ptolemy+pandi+mandala&dq=Ptolemy+pandi+mandala&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwidsd6un4TZAhXB_ywKHbx-Be4Q6AEIXzAH|title=The Cyclopaedia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia|last=Balfur|first=Edward|date=1968|publisher=Akademische Druck- u. Verlagsanstalt|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=105|language=en}}</ref>\n* [[Strabo]] states that an Indian king called Pandion sent [[Augustus Caesar]] \"presents and gifts of honour\".<ref name=\":7\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=te1sqTzTxD8C&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72 The First Spring: The Golden Age of India \u2013 Abraham Eraly \u2013 Google Books]. Books.google.co.in. Retrieved on 12 July 2013.</ref><ref name=\":162\"/> The 1st-century [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] historian [[Nicolaus of Damascus]] met, at [[Antioch]], the ambassador sent by a king from India \"named Pandion or, according to others, Porus\" to [[Caesar Augustus]] around 13 CE (Strabo XV.4 and 73).<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0239%3Abook%3D15%3Achapter%3D1%3Asection%3D73 Strabo, Geography, BOOK XV., CHAPTER I., section 73]. Perseus.tufts.edu. Retrieved on 12 July 2013.</ref><ref>Keay, p121</ref>\n* The [[Roman emperor]] [[Julian the Apostate|Julian]] received an embassy from a Pandya about 361 CE.<ref name=\":3\" />\n* Chinese historian [[Yu Huan]] in his 3rd-century CE text, the ''Weil\u00fce'', mentions the Panyue kingdom: \n{{cquote|...the kingdom of Panyue is also called ''Hanyuewang''. It is several thousand li to the southeast of [[Tianzhu (India)|Tianzhu]] (northern India)...The inhabitants are small; they are the same height as the Chinese...}} \nScholar John E. Hill identified Panyue as Pandya kingdom.<ref name=\"weilue\">Hill, John</ref> However, others have identified it with an ancient state located in modern [[Burma]]<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CZQMAQAAMAAJ|title=Between winds and clouds: the making of Yunnan (second century BCE to twentieth century CE)|author=Bin Yang|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0-231-14254-0}}</ref> or [[Assam]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dbjLO5l1PCkC&pg=PA12|title=A History of Sino-Indian Relations|author=Yukteshwar Kumar|publisher=APH Publishing|year=2005|isbn=978-81-7648-798-6|page=12}}</ref>\n* The Chinese traveler [[Xuanzang]] mentions a kingdom further south from [[Kanchipuram]], a kingdom named ''Malakutta'', identified with [[Madurai]] described by his Buddhist friends at [[Kanchipuram]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=8XXGhAL1WKcC&pg=PA453&dq=Hiuen+Tsang+malakotta&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivsMHL4oXZAhUG6CwKHdjEBFwQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Hiuen%20Tsang%20malakotta&f=false|title=The Early History of India|last=Smith|first=Vincent A.|date=1999|publisher=Atlantic Publishers & Dist|year=|isbn=9788171566181|location=|pages=453|language=en}}</ref>\n* In the later part of the 13th century (in 1288 and 1293 CE) [[Venetian Republic|Venetian]] traveller [[Marco Polo]] visited the Pandya kingdom and left a vivid description of the land and its people.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=adpkHQ9SCq0C&pg=PA5 Travel and ethnology in the Renaissance: South India through European eyes, Joan-Pau Rubi\u00e9s]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=11FYACaVySoC&pg=PA9 Muslim identity, print culture, and the Dravidian factor in Tamil Nadu, J. B. Prashant More]</ref>\n{{cquote|The darkest man is here the most highly esteemed and considered better than the others who are not so dark. Let me add that in very truth these people portray and depict their gods and their idols black and their devils white as snow.  For they say that god and all the saints are black and the devils are all white. That is why they portray them as I have described.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-yEfRP0RwgC&pg=PA110 Layers of blackness: colourism in the African diaspora, Deborah Gabriel]</ref>\n}}\n\n== Political history ==\n[[File:An aerial view of Madurai city from atop of Meenakshi Amman temple.jpg|thumb|800px|center|An aerial view of [[Madurai]] city from [[Meenakshi Temple|Meenakshi Amman Temple]] |alt=aerial image of a temple campus]]\n\n===Early Pandyas (c. 3rd century BCE \u2013 c. 3rd century CE)===\n{{Main| Early Pandyan Kingdom}}\n[[File:A_sunrise_over_Vaigai_River_in_Madurai_Tamil_Nadu_India.jpg|alt=|thumb|290x290px|[[Vaigai River]] in Madurai]]\n[[Maurya Empire|Maurya]] emperor [[Ashoka|Asoka]] (3rd century BCE) seems to have been on friendly terms with the people of south India and Sri Lanka (the [[Chola dynasty|Cholas]], the Pandyas, the [[Satiyaputras|Satiya Putras]], the [[Chera dynasty|Kerala Putras]] and the [[Tamraparni]]s). There are no indications that Asoka tried to conquer the extreme south India (the Tamilakam \u2013 the Abode of the Tamils).{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=184}}\n\nThe three chiefly lines of the early historic south India \u2013 the Cheras, Pandyas and Cholas \u2013 were known as the mu-vendar (\"the three vendars\"). They traditionally based at their original headquarters in the interior [[Tamil Nadu]] ([[Karur]], [[Madurai]] and [[Uraiyur]] respectively).<ref name=\":162\"/> The powerful chiefdoms of the three ventar dominated the political and economic life of early historic south India.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=231}} The frequent conflicts between the Chera, the Chola and the Pandya are well documented in ancient (the [[Sangam literature|Sangam]]) Tamil poetry.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=242}} The Cheras, Cholas and Pandyas also controlled the ports of [[Muziris|Muziris (Muchiri)]], [[Korkai]] and Kaveri respectively (for the trade with the [[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] world).<ref name=\":162\"/> The gradual shift from chiefdoms to kingdoms seems to have occurred in the following period.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=231}}[[File:Temple between hill symbols and elephant coin of the Pandyas Sri Lanka 1st century CE.jpg|thumb|Pandya coin with temple between hills and elephant (Sri Lanka -1st century CE) ([[British Museum]]).]]The famous inscription of king [[Kharavela]] at Hathigumpha (mid-first century BCE<ref name=\":162\"/>) mentions the defeat of a confederacy of the \"Tramira\" countries which had been a threat to Kalinga. It also remembers the precious pearls brought to the capital as booty from the \"Pandya\" realm.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=211-212}} The Pandya chiefdom was famous for its pearl fisheries and silk industry.<ref name=\":162\"/> [[Korkai]] and [[Alagankulam]] are believed to have been the exchange centres of the Pandyas. Korkai, a port at the mouth of the river Tambraparni, was linked to the famous pearl fisheries and Alagankulam was also developed as a port.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=229}}\n\nA number of coins attributed to early historic Pandyas are found from the region.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=242}} Inscriptions, datable to c. 2nd century BCE, recording royal grants \u2013 both from royals and wealthy commoners \u2013 were also discovered from the Pandya country.<ref name=\":19\">Thapar, Romila. ''Southern Indian kingdoms'' \"India\". Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Online. https://www.britannica.com/place/India/The-Shunga-kingdom#ref46870</ref>\n\nThe Pandya seems to be the most prominent of the three \"ventar\" rulers. There are even references to a Pandya queen from 3rd century BCE representing a confederacy of the Tamil countries.<ref name=\":162\"/> [[Madurai]], in south Tamil Nadu, was the most important cultural centre in south India as the core of the Tamil speakers.<ref name=\":19\" /> Megalithic relics such as menhirs, dolmens, urn burials, stone circles and rock-cut chambers/passages can be found in south India. Burial goods include iron objects, ivory ornaments, Black-and-Red Ware and even some [[Roman Empire|Roman Imperial]] coins.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=230}} The so-called \"velir\" hill chieftains are assumed to be associated with these megalithic burials.{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=231}}\n\nGreek and Latin accounts (early centuries CE), coins with legends in Tamil-Brahmi script, and Tamil-Brahmi inscriptions suggest the continuity of the Pandya dynasty from the 3rd century BCE to early centuries CE.<ref name=\":17\" /> The early Pandyas, along with the Cheras and the Cholas, were eventually displaced by the [[Kalabhra dynasty]].{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=327}}\n\n''The following is a partial list of Pandya rulers from early historic south India:<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=FjxuAAAAMAAJ&q=A+History+of+South+India+from+the+Early+Times+to+the+Fall+of+Vijayanagar+nilakanta+sastri&dq=A+History+of+South+India+from+the+Early+Times+to+the+Fall+of+Vijayanagar+nilakanta+sastri&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi94vSGs5nZAhVFCiwKHV-nBooQ6AEIKDAA|title=A history of South India from prehistoric times to the fall of Vijayanagar|last=Sastri|first=Kallidaikurichi Aiyah Nilakanta|date=1976|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=22\u201325|language=en}}</ref>'' The early Tami poems mention twelve Pandya rulers.<ref name=\":17\" />\n[[File:S-TN-71 Vettuvan Koil Tuticorin.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Vettuvan Koil|Vettuvan koil]], Kalugumalai, Tuticorin. Pandya kingdom, 8th century CE|alt=]]<blockquote>\n* Koon Pandya\n*[[Nedunjeliyan I]] (\"Aariyap Padai Kadantha\")\n* Puda-pandya\n* \"Palyagasalai\" Mudukudumi Peruvaludi<ref name=\":18\" />\n*[[Nedunjeliyan II]]\n* Nan Maran\n* Nedunj Cheliyan III (\"Talaiyaalanganathu Seruvendra\")<ref name=\":18\" />\n* Maran Valudi\n* Kadalan Valuthi\n* Musiri Mutriya Cheliyan\n* Ukkirap Peruvaludi\n</blockquote>\n\n===Pandya revival (7th\u201310th centuries CE)===\n[[File:FourArmedVishnuPandyaDynasty8-9thCentury.jpg|left|thumb|Enthroned god [[Vishnu]], Pandya dynasty, second half of the 8th\u2013early 9th century CE ([[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City)]]\n[[File:The Hindu Saint Manikkavacakar LACMA AC1997.16.1 (1 of 12).jpg|thumb|[[Manikkavacakar|Manikkavachakar]], minister of Pandya king Varaguna II (9th century CE) (early 12th century) Los Angeles County Museum of Art]]\n[[File:Double fish Pandyan relief, Koneswaram.jpg|thumb|250px|Jatavarman Veera Pandya II's double fish carp black granite [[Relief|bas-relief]] of the [[Koneswaram temple]] in [[Trincomalee]], reminiscent of the [[Pandya coinage|dynasty's coinage]] symbols found on the island from the [[Pre-modern coinage in Sri Lanka|pre-modern era]], installed after defeating the usurper [[Chandrabhanu]] of [[Tambralinga]]. Pandya affairs in Northern Sri Lanka grew stronger following the intervention of Srimara Srivallabha in 815 CE<ref name=\"Indrapala 2007 324\">{{cite book | last = Indrapala | first = Karthigesu | title = The evolution of an ethnic identity: The Tamils in Sri Lanka C. 300 BCE to C. 1200 CE| publisher = Vijitha Yapa | year = 2007 | page=324|location = Colombo | isbn = 978-955-1266-72-1}}</ref> ]]\nThe Pandya kingdom was revived by king Kadungon (r. 590\u2013620 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}) towards the end of the 6th century CE.<ref name=\":3\" />{{sfn|Romila Thapar|2003|p=331}} In the [[Velvikudi inscription]], a later copper-plate, Kadungon appears as the \"destroyer\" of the \"anti-Brahmanical\" [[Kalabhra dynasty|Kalabhra]] kings.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} With the decline of the Kalabhra dynasty, the Pandyas grew steadily in power and territory. With the [[Cholas]] in obscurity in [[Uraiyur]], the Tamil country was divided between the [[Pallavas|Pallavas of Kanchi]] and the Pandyas of Madurai.\n\nFrom 6th century to 9th century CE, the [[Chalukyas of Badami]], the [[Pallavas of Kanchi]], and Pandyas of Madurai dominated the politics of south India. The Badami Chalukyas were eventually replaced by the [[Rashtrakuta dynasty|Rashtrakutas]] in the Deccan.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=84-85}} The Pandyas took on the growing Pallava ambitions in south India, and from time to time they also joined in alliances with the kingdoms of the Deccan Plateau (such as with the [[Western Ganga dynasty|Gangas of Talakad]] in late 8th century CE).<ref name=\":19\" /> In the middle of the 9th century, the Pandyas had managed to advance as far as [[Kumbakonam]] (north-east of Tanjore on the Kollidam river).<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nSendan (r. 654\u201370 CE), the third king of the Pandyas of Madurai, is known for expanding his kingdom to the [[Chera dynasty|Chera country]] (western Tamil Nadu and central [[Kerala]]). Arikesari Maravarman (r. 670\u2013700 CE), the fourth Pandya ruler, is known for his battles against the [[Pallava dynasty|Pallavas of Kanchi]]. Pallava king Narasimhavarman I (r. 630\u201368 CE), the famous conqurer of [[Badami]], claimed to have defeated the Pandyas. [[Chalukya dynasty|Chalukya]] king Paramesvaravarman I \"Vikramaditya\" (r. 670\u2013700 CE) is known to have fought battles with the Pallavas, the Gangas, and probably with the Pandyas too, on the Kaveri basin.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}\n\nKirtivarman II (r. 744/5\u201355 CE), the last Chalukya king, managed to lose to his southern countries as a result of his battles with the Pandyas. Pandya kings Maravarman Rajasimha I (r. 730\u201365 CE) and Nedunjadaiyan/Varagunavarman I (r. 765\u2013815 CE) threatened Pallava king Nandivarman II Pallavamalla (r. 731\u201396 CE) who had managed to defeat the Gangas in around 760 CE. Varagunavarman I invaded the Pallava country, conquered the Kongu country (western Tamil Nadu) and [[Venad]]u (south Kerala). King Srimara Srivallabha (r. 815\u201362 CE) sailed to Sri Lanka, subjugated king Sena I, and sacked his capital [[Anuradhapura]] (the Panya invasion of Sri Lanka followed a period of vassalage).{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} However, Srimara Srivallabha was soon overpowerd by Pallava king Nripatunga (r. 859\u201399 CE). Sena II, the king of Sri Lanka, invaded the Pandya country, sacked Madurai and chose Varagunavarman II (r. c. 862\u2013880 CE<ref name=\":232\"/>) as the new king soon after.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} It is proposed that the start of the [[Malayalam calendar|Kollam Era]], the Kerala calendar, in 825 CE marked the liberation of Venadu from Pandya control.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=89}}\n\nDuring the rule of Dantivarman (r. 796\u2013847 CE), the Pallava territory was reduced by the encroachment from the Pandyas from the south (and Rashtrakutas and the [[Telugu Cholas|Telugu-Chodas]] from north). Pallava king Nandivarman III (r. 846\u201369 CE) was able to defeat the Pandyas and Telugu-Chodas (and even the Rashtrakutas) with the help of the Gangas and the emerging Cholas.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}\n\n''Chronological list of the Pandya kings.''<ref name=\":232\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 165.</ref>\n\n* [[Kadungon]] (r. c. 590\u2013620 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\"/>)\n* Maravarman [[Avani Sulamani|Avanisulamani]] (r. c. 620-645 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* Cheliyan Sendan/Chendan (r. c. 654\u2013670 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Arikesari Maravarman|Arikesari Maravarman (Parankusan)]] (r. c. 670\u2013700 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Kochadaiyan Ranadhiran|Ko Chadaiyan Ranadhira]] (r. c. 700\u2013730 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Maravarman Rajasimha I]] (r. c. 730\u2013765 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* Parantaka Nedunjadaiyan/Varaguna-varman I{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}} (r. c. 765\u2013815 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Srimara Srivallabha|Maravarman Srimara Srivallabha]] (r. c. 815\u2013862 CE{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=85-87}}<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Varagunavarman II|Varaguna-varman II]] (r. c. 862\u2013880 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* Parantaka Viranarayana (r. c. 880\u2013900/905 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n* [[Maravarman Rajasimha III]] (r. c. 900\u2013920 CE<ref name=\":232\" />)\n\n<br />[[File:Jaina_abode_Kalugumalai.JPG|thumb|600x600px|[[Kalugumalai Jain Beds|Kalugumalai Jain beds]], Pandya kingdom, king Jatila Parantaka Nedunjadayan (8th century CE)|alt=|center]]\n\n===Under Chola influence (10th\u201313th centuries)===\n[[File:South_India_in_12th_century_AD.jpg|thumb|328x328px|Pandya country in the [[Chola dynasty|Chola Empire]] (12th century)]]\nWhile the Pandyas and the Rashtrakutas were busy engaging the Pallavas, with the Gangas and the Simhalas (Sri Lanka) also in the mix, the Cholas emerged from the Kaveri delta and took on the chieftains of [[Thanjavur]]{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=121-123}} (the [[Muthuraja|Mutharaiyar]] chieftain had transferred their loyalty from the Pallava to the Pandya<ref name=\":24\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 167\u201368.</ref>). The [[Chola dynasty|Chola]] king [[Vijayalaya Chola|Vijayalaya]] conquered [[Thanjavur]] by defeating the [[Muthuraja|Mutharaiyar]] chieftain around c. 850 CE.<ref name=\":24\" /> The Pandya control north of the Kaveri river was severely weakened by this move (and straightened the position of the Pallava ruler Nripatunga).<ref name=\":24\" />  Pandya ruler [[Varagunavarman II|Varaguna-varman II]] (r. c. 862\u2013880 CE<ref name=\":232\"/>) responded by marching into the Chola country and facing a formidable alliance of Pallava prince Aparajita, the Chola king Aditya I and the Ganga king Prithvipati I. The Pandya king suffered a crushing defeat (c. 880 CE) in a battle fought near Kumbakonam.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nBy c. 897 CE, Chola king [[Aditya I]] was the master of the old Pallava, Ganga and Kongu countries. It is a possibility that Aditya I conquered the Kongu country from the Pandya king Parantaka Viranarayana (r. 880\u2013900 CE).<ref name=\":24\" /> [[Parantaka I]], successor to Aditya, invaded the Pandya territories in 910 CE and captured Madurai from king Maravarman Rajasimha II (hence the title \"Madurai Konda\").<ref name=\":24\" />  Rajasimha II received help from the Sri Lankan king Kassapa V, still got defeated by [[Parantaka I]] in the battle of Vellur, and fled to Sri Lanka. Rajasimha then found refuge in the Chera country, leaving even his royal insignia in Sri Lanka, the home of his mother.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nThe Cholas were defeated by a Rashtrakuta-lead confederacy in the [[battle of Takkolam]] in 949 CE.<ref name=\":252\"/> By mid-950s, the Chola kingdom had shrunk to the size of a small principality (its vassals in the extreme south had proclaimed their independence).<ref name=\":252\"/> It is a possibility that Pandya ruler Vira Pandya defeated Chola king Gandaraditya and claimed independence.<ref name=\":252\"/> Chola ruler [[Parantaka Chola II|Sundara Parantaka II]] (r. 957\u201373) responded by defeating Vira Pandya in two battles (and Chola prince [[Aditya II]] killed Vira Pandya on the second occasion). The Pandyas were assisted by Sri Lanka forces of king Mahinda IV.<ref name=\":252\"/>\n\nChola emperor [[Rajaraja I]] (r. 985\u20131014 CE) is known to have attacked the Pandyas.<ref name=\":19\" /> He fought against an alliance of the Pandya, [[Chera dynasty|Chera]] and Sri Lankan kings, and defeated the Cheras and \"deprived\" the Pandyas of their ancient capital Madurai.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}} Emperor [[Rajendra Chola I|Rajendra I]] continued to occupy the Pandya kingdom, and even appointed a series of Chola viceroys with the title \"Chola Pandya\" to rule from Madurai (over Pandya and Western Chera/Kerala countries). The very of beginning of Chola emperor [[Kulottunga I|Kulottunga]]'s rule (r. from 1070 CE) was marked by the loss of Sri Lanka and a rebellion in the Pandya country.{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}}\n\nThe second half of the 12th century witnessed a major internal crisis in the Pandya country (between princes Parakrama Pandya and Kulasekhara Pandya). The neighbouring kingdoms of Sri Lanka, under [[Parakramabahu I]], [[Venad|Venadu Chera/Kerala]], under the Kulasekharas,{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}} and the Cholas, under [[Rajadhiraja Chola II|Rajadhiraja II]] and [[Kulothunga Chola III|Kulottunga III]], joinined in and took sides with any of the two princes or their kins.<ref>Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 187-90.</ref>{{sfn|Noboru Karashima|2014|p=122-124}}\n\n''The following list gives the names of the Pandya kings who were active during the 10th century and the first half of 11th century.'' <blockquote>\n* Sundara Pandya I\n* Vira Pandya I\n* Vira Pandya II\n* Amarabhujanga Tivrakopa\n* Jatavarman Sundara Chola Pandya\n* Maravarman Vikrama Chola Pandya\n* Maravarman Parakrama Chola Pandya\n* Jatavarman Chola Pandya\n* Srivallabha Manakulachala (1101\u20131124 CE)\n* Maravarman Srivallabha (1132\u20131161 CE)\n*[[Parakrama Pandyan I|Parakrama I]] (1161\u20131162 CE)\n* Kulasekara III\n* Vira Pandya III\n* Jatavarman Srivallabha (1175\u20131180 CE)\n*[[Jatavarman Kulasekaran I|Jatavarman Kulasekara I]] (1190\u20131216 CE)<ref name=\"sen2\">{{Cite book|title=A Textbook of Medieval Indian History|last=Sen|first=Sailendra|publisher=Primus Books|year=2013|isbn=978-9-38060-734-4|pages=45\u201346}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n=== Pandya empire (13th\u201314th centuries) ===\n\nThe Pandya empire included extensive territories, at times including large portions of south India and [[Sri Lanka]]. The Pandya king at Madurai controlled these vast regions through the collateral family branches subject to [[Madurai]].<ref name=\":3\" /> The kingdom was shared among several male royals of the family, one of them enjoying control over the rest.<ref name=\":2\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 208-11.</ref>\n\nThe 13th century saw the rise of seven prime Pandya \"Lord Emperors\" (Ellarkku Nayanar \u2013 Lord of All), who ruled the kingdom alongside other Pandya royals. Their power reached its zenith under [[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan|Jatavarman Sundara I]] in the middle of the 13th century.<ref name=\":27\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA459&dq=maravarman&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE24jHtJnZAhVCCCwKHUbmAuoQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=maravarman&f=false|title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization|last=Sen|first=Sailendra Nath|date=1999|publisher=New Age International|year=|isbn=9788122411980|location=|pages=458|language=en}}</ref>  <blockquote>\n*[[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan|Maravarman Sundara Pandya I]] (1216\u20131238 CE)\n* Sundaravarman Kulasekara II (1238\u20131240 CE)\n*[[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan II|Maravarman Sundara Pandya II]] (1238\u20131251 CE)\n*[[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan|Jatavarman Sundara Pandya I]] (1251\u20131268 CE)\n*[[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Maravarman Kulasekara Pandya I]] (1268\u20131310 CE)\n* Sundara Pandya IV (1309\u20131327 CE)\n* Vira Pandya IV (1309\u20131345 CE)\n</blockquote>The foundation for the Pandya supremacy in south India was laid by [[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan|Maravarman Sundara I]] early in the 13th century.<ref name=\":27\" /> He succeeded his older brother Jatavarman Kulasekhara in 1216.<ref name=\":9\">Sastri, K. A. Nilakanta. (1958, second ed.) ''A History of South India from Prehistoric Times to the Fall of Vijayanagar.'' Madras, Oxford University Press. 203-07.</ref> He invaded the Chola country, sacked [[Uraiyur]] and [[Thanjavur]], and drove the Chola king [[Kulothunga Chola III|Kulothunga III]] into exile.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=XNxiN5tzKOgC&pg=PA411&dq=kulottunga+hoysala+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ0-q015nZAhUFEiwKHVktBXwQ6AEIMDAB#v=onepage&q=kulottunga%20hoysala%20pandya&f=false|title=Ancient India|last=Majumdar|first=[[R. C. Majumdar|Ramesh Chandra]]|date=1977|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|year=|isbn=9788120804364|location=|pages=411|language=en}}</ref> The Chola king subsequently made a formal submission to Maravarman Sundara I and acknowledged his overlordship.<ref name=\":9\" /> Attempts by the next Chola king [[Rajaraja Chola III|Rajaraja III]] (1216 \u2013 46 CE<ref name=\":302\"/>) for self-rule (to stop the Pandya invasion into the Chola country<ref name=\":302\"/>), with the help of the [[Hoysala Empire|Hoysalas]] king Narasimha II (r. 1220 \u2013 1238 CE), resulted in a battle between the Pandya and Hoysala forces at Mahendramangalam on the [[Kaveri|Kaveri Valley]]. Maravarman Sundara I was defeated and Rajaraja III was restored in the Chola country.<ref name=\":9\" /> Sometime later Chola prince [[Rajendra Chola III|Rajendra III]] attacked the Pandyas and defeated two Pandya royals including [[Maravarman Sundara Pandyan II|Maravarman Sundara II]].<ref name=\":9\" /> Hoysala king [[Vira Someshwara|Somesvara]] (r. 1233 \u2013 1267 CE<ref name=\":302\"/>) then came to the aid of the Pandyas, defeated Rajendra III and then made peace with the Cholas.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Pandya revival under Jatavarman Sundara Pandya ====\n[[Jatavarman Sundara Pandyan I|Jatavarman Sundara I]] ascended the Pandya throne in 1251 CE.<ref name=\":302\"/> He led his army to the Chola country (even as far as [[Nellore]]), to [[Sri Lanka]] and to south [[Kerala]].<ref name=\":302\"/> He was also successful in confining the Hoysala control to the Mysore Plateau (the ancient Chola country was now overrun by the Pandyas<ref name=\":302\"/>).<ref name=\":9\" /> [[Kanchipuram|Kanchi]] functioned as the second major city in the kingdom.<ref name=\":9\" /> In his conquests, Jatavarman Sundara I was assisted by number of Pandya royals such as Jatavarman Vira Pandya.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nJatavarman Sundara I subdued Rajendra III around 1258\u20131260 CE and made him pay tribute.<ref name=\":0\" /> The rule of the Cholas ended c. 1279 with Rajendra III.<ref name=\":302\"/> The Pandya attacked the Hoysalas in the Kaveri and captured the fort of Kannanur Koppam.<ref name=\":9\" /> Hoysala king [[Vira Someshwara|Somesvara]] was forced to fall back into the Mysore Plateau.<ref name=\":9\" /> The Hoysala king, pressed by enemies from north and south, \"assigned\" the southern half of his kingdom to his younger son Ramanatha (r. 1254\u20131292<ref name=\":302\"/>). [[Vira Someshwara|Somesvara]] was eventually killed by the Pandya in 1262 CE.<ref name=\":9\" /> Ramanatha managed to recover Kannanur and hold against the Pandya power.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=Wk4_ICH_g1EC&pg=PA459&dq=maravarman&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjE24jHtJnZAhVCCCwKHUbmAuoQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=maravarman&f=false|title=Ancient Indian History and Civilization|last=Sen|first=Sailendra Nath|date=1999|publisher=New Age International|year=|isbn=9788122411980|location=|pages=439|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=rB7jAAAAMAAJ&q=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+%22rajendra+III%22&dq=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+%22rajendra+III%22&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVwZuq_ZnZAhVBuSwKHTrDCSIQ6AEIPzAD|title=Proceedings \u2013 Indian History Congress|last=Congress|first=Indian History|date=1957|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=186|language=en}}</ref> Jatavarman Sundara I also came into conflict with the [[Kadava dynasty|Kadava]] ruler [[Kopperunchinga II|Kopperunjinga II]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/delhisultanate00bhar|quote=jatavarman kadava.|title=The History and Culture of the Indian People: The struggle for empire|last=Majumdar|first=Ramesh Chandra|last2=Bhavan|first2=Bharatiya Vidya|date=1966|publisher=Bharatiya Vidya Bhavan|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/delhisultanate00bhar/page/257 257]|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":9\" /> It seems that Bana (Magadai) and Kongu countries came under the Pandya rule during the wars against the Hoysalas and the Kadavas.<ref name=\":9\" /> Jatavarman Sundara I also fought the Kakatiya ruler Ganapati (1199-1262<ref name=\":302\"/>).<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Sri Lanka]] was invaded by Jatavarman Sundara I in 1258<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=HBQ1AQAAIAAJ&dq=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+chandrabhanu&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Jatavarman+sundara+pandyan+|title=The collapse of the Rajarata civilization in Ceylon and the drift to the south-west: a symposium|last=Intirap\u0101l\u0101|first=K\u0101rttik\u0113cu|date=1971|publisher=Ceylon Studies Seminar, University of Ceylon|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=96|language=en}}</ref> and on his behalf by his younger brother [[Jatavarman Vira Pandyan II|Jatavarman Vira II]] between 1262 and 1264 CE.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=7yULAQAAIAAJ&q=pandya+power+telugu&dq=pandya+power+telugu&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6reCI0ZnZAhXDlCwKHS2SCms4ChDoAQhlMAg|title=Andhra Pradesh District Gazetteers: Prakasam|last=(India)|first=Andhra Pradesh|date=2000|publisher=Director of Print. and Stationery at the Government Secretariat Press; [copies can be from: Government Publication Bureau, Andhra Pradesh]|language=en}}</ref> The island was again invaded and defeated by Jatavarman Vira II in 1270 CE.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=aLYoDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=editions:uCBuXG9qshEC&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwidy9XugZrZAhXMWCwKHRWqBSMQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=chandrabhanu&f=false|title=The Hutchinson Dictionary of Ancient and Medieval Warfare|last=Connolly|first=Peter|last2=Gillingham|first2=John|last3=Lazenby|first3=John|date=2016-05-13|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781135936747|location=|pages=100|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSundara Pandya I (died in 1268) was succeeded by [[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Maravarman Kulasekara I]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Around 1279 the combined force of Hoysala king Ramanatha and [[Rajendra Chola III|Rajendra III]] was defeated by Maravarman Kulasekara I.<ref name=\":2\" /> Maravarman Kulasekara I, now virtually unchallenged, ruled over the Chola country and southern Tamil speaking portions of Hoysala kingdom. He also invaded Sri Lanka, ruled by Bhuvanaikabahu I, \"carried away to the Pandya country the venerable Tooth Relic\", and the wealth of the island.<ref name=\":2\" /> Sri Lanka remained under Pandya control till c. 1308-09 CE.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n====Decline of Pandya empire====\nAfter the death of [[Maravarman Kulasekara Pandyan I|Maravarman Kulasekhara I]] (1310), his sons Vira Pandya IV and Sundara Pandya IV fought a war of succession for control of the empire. It seems that Maravarman Kulasekhara wanted Vira Pandya to succeed him (who inturn was defeated by Sundara Pandya after a short period of time).<ref>{{cite book|title=Muslim Identity, Print Culture, and the Dravidian Factor in Tamil Nadu|author=J. B. Prashant More|publisher=Orient Blackswan, 2004|page=10}}</ref> Unfortunately, the Pandya civil war coincided with the [[Khalji dynasty|Khalji]] raids in south India.<ref>{{cite book|title=Sri Varadarajaswami Temple, Kanchi: A Study of Its History, Art and Architecture|author=K.V. Raman|publisher=Abhinav Publications, 2003|page=24}}</ref> Taking advantage of the political situation, the neighbouring [[Hoysala]] king [[Veera Ballala III|Ballala III]] invaded the Pandya territory. However, Ballala had to retreat to his capital, when Khalji general [[Malik Kafur]] invaded his kingdom at the same time.{{sfn|Banarsi Prasad Saksena|1992|p=412}} After subjugating Ballala III, the Khalji forces marched to the Pandya territory in March 1311.{{sfn|Banarsi Prasad Saksena|1992|p=414}} The Pandya brothers fled their headquarters, and the Khaljis pursued them unsuccessfully.{{sfn|Banarsi Prasad Saksena|1992|pp=416\u2013417}}{{sfn|Kishori Saran Lal|1950|pp=208\u2013213}} By late April 1311, the Khaljis gave up their plans to pursue the Pandya princes, and returned to Delhi with the plunder.{{sfn|Kishori Saran Lal|1950|p=212}}{{sfn|Peter Jackson|2003|p=207}} By 1312 the Pandya control over south [[Kerala]] was also lost.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAfter departure of the Khaljis, Vira and Sundara Pandya resumed their conflict. Sundara Pandya was defeated, and sought help from the Khaljis. With their help, he regained control of the [[South Arcot]] region by 1314.{{sfn|Peter Jackson|2003|p=207}} Subsequently, there were two more expeditions from the sultanate in 1314 led by [[Khusro Khan]] and in 1323 by Ulugh Khan ([[Muhammad bin Tughluq]]) under sultan [[Ghiyath al-Din Tughluq]].{{sfn|Peter Jackson|2003|p=207}}\n\nThe family quarrels and the sultanate invasions shattered the Pandya empire beyond revival<ref name=\":3\" /> and coinage discoveries made imply that the Pandyas were left with the old South Arcot region.<ref name=\":12\" /> In 1323, the [[Jaffna Kingdom|Jaffna kingdom]] declared its independence from the crumbling Pandya influence.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":11\" />\n\nWhile the previous sultanate raids were content with plunder, the [[Tughlaq dynasty|Tughluqs]] under Ulugh Khan (later [[Muhammad bin Tughluq]]<ref name=\":31\" />) annexed the former Pandya dominions to the sultanate as the province of Ma'bar. Most of south India came under the sultanate rule and was divided into five provinces \u2013 Devagiri, Tiling, [[Kampili]], [[Halebidu|Dorasamudra]] and Ma'bar.<ref name=\":12\">Nilakanta Sastri, P.213</ref> [[Jalaluddin Ahsan Khan|Jalal ud-Din Hasan Khan]] was appointed governor of the newly created southern-most Ma'bar province.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=uCYdAAAAMAAJ&q=Vira+Someshwara+pandya&dq=Vira+Someshwara+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjpsvuK25nZAhVIEiwKHWYlA7gQ6AEIXzAI|title=Karnataka, History, Administration & Culture|last=Muthanna|first=I. M.|date=1962|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=89|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w6zkx_Ck3FwC&pg=PA171|title=South India and Her Muhammadan Invaders|last=Aiyangar|first=Krishnaswami S.|publisher=Asian Educational Services, 1991 \u2013 India, South|year=1991|isbn=9788120605367|pages=67\u201368,110\u2013111,167,171\u2013174}}</ref> In c. 1334, Jalal ud-Din Hasan Khan declared his independence and created [[Madurai Sultanate|Madurai sultanate]].<ref name=\":31\" /> The Pandyas shifted their capital to [[Tenkasi]] and continued to rule a small area until the end of the 16th century.<ref name=\":31\" />\n\n[[Bukka Raya I]] of [[Vijayanagara Empire|Vijayanagara empire]] conquered the city of Madurai in c. 1370,<ref name=\":31\" /> imprisoned the sultan, released and restored Arcot's prince Sambuva Raya to the throne. Bukka Raya I appointed his son Veera Kumara Kampana as the viceroy of the Tamil region. Meanwhile, Madurai sultanate was replaced by the Nayak governors of [[Vijayanagara]] in 1378.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A Comprehensive History of India: Comprehensive history of medieval India|last=Puri|first=B. N.|last2=Das|first2=M. N.|date=2003-12-01|publisher=Sterling Publishers Pvt. Ltd|year=|isbn=9788120725089|location=|pages=90\u201391|language=en}}</ref> In 1529 the Nayak governors declared independence and established [[Madurai Nayak dynasty]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Economy and society==\n[[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] merchants frequented the [[ancient Tamil country]], present day [[Southern India|south India]] and [[Sri Lanka]], securing contacts with the [[Tamil people|Tamil]] chiefdoms of the Pandya, [[Chola Empire|Chola]] and [[Chera Empire|Chera]] families.<ref name=\":26\" /> The western sailors also established a number of trading settlements on the harbours of the ancient Tamil region.<ref name=\":26\" />\n\nThe trade with South Asia by the [[Greco-Roman world]] flourished since the time of the [[Ptolemaic dynasty]]<ref name=\"Lindsay1\">Lindsay (2006) p. 101</ref> a few decades before the start of the [[Common Era]] and remained long after the fall of the [[Western Roman Empire]].<ref name=\"Curtin1\">Curtin 1984: 100</ref><ref name=\"The cyclop\u00e6dia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia\">The cyclop\u00e6dia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia By Edward Balfour</ref> The contacts between south India and the Middle East continued even after the [[Byzantium]]'s loss of the ports of [[Egypt]] and the [[Red Sea]]<ref name=\"Holl1\">Holl 2003: 9</ref> in the 7th century CE.\n\nThe Pandya country, located at the extreme south-western tip of [[South Asia]], served as an important meeting point throughout the history of the India. The location was economically and geopolitically significant as a key point connecting the shipping between [[Southeast Asia]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\n===Coinage===\n{{See also|Pandya coinage}}\n\nThe early coins of [[Tamilakam]] bore the symbols of the [[Three Crowned Kings]], the tiger, the fish and the bow, representing the symbols of the Cholas, Pandyas and Cheras.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=PMVWAAAAMAAJ&dq=pandya+gold+coin&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=pandya+fish+coin|title=Early Indian indigenous coins|last=Sircar|first=Dineshchandra|date=1970|publisher=University of Calcutta|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=98|language=en}}</ref> Coins of Pandyas bear the legend of different Pandya ruler in different times. The Pandyas had [[File:Coin Pandya Bull Obv 2.jpg|thumb|One of the early coins of the Pandyas showing their emblem of the two fishes.]]issued silver [[Punch-marked coins|punch-marked]] and die struck copper coins in the early period.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=9VFmAAAAMAAJ&q=pandya+silver+coin&dq=pandya+silver+coin&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZrt65srXZAhVR3aQKHelDBwcQ6AEIWzAH|title=The Journal of the Numismatic Society of India|last=|first=|date=2005|publisher=Numismatic Society of India|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=67|language=en}}</ref> A few gold coins were attributed to the Pandya rulers of this period. These coins bore the image of fish, singly or in pairs, which where their emblem.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=PMVWAAAAMAAJ&q=pandya+gold+coin&dq=pandya+gold+coin&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwic_LK5s7XZAhUP_qQKHbhoC3EQ6AEIbTAJ|title=Early Indian indigenous coins|last=Sircar|first=Dineshchandra|date=1970|publisher=University of Calcutta|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=96|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSome of the coins had the names Sundara, Sundara Pandya or merely the letter 'Su' were etched. Some of the coins bore a boar with the legend of 'Vira-Pandya.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=yyix9TSozmAC&pg=PA49&dq=pandya+coin+sundara&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUuduNtbXZAhVECewKHQpgAosQ6AEINzAC#v=onepage&q=pandya%20coin%20sundara&f=false|title=Dravidian kingdoms and list of Pandiyan coins|last=Savariroyan|first=Pandit D.|date=2004|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120617520|location=|pages=48\u201349|language=en}}</ref> It had been said that those coins were issued by the Pandyas and the feudatories of the Cholas but could not be attributed to any particular king.\n\nThe coins of Pandyas were basically square. Those coins were etched with elephant on one side and the other side remained blank. The inscription on the silver and gold coins during the Pandyas, were in [[Tamil-Brahmi]] and the copper coins bore the Tamil legends.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=JFAaAAAAYAAJ&q=pandya+coin+script&dq=pandya+coin+script&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwir05OctrXZAhWCKewKHQXcCd8Q6AEITjAF|title=Numismatic Studies, Vol|last=Shastri|first=Ajay Mitra|last2=Kumar|first2=Manmohan S.|date=1996-01-01|publisher=Harman Publishing House|year=|isbn=9788185151922|location=|pages=46|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe coins of the Pandyas, which bore the fish symbols, were termed as 'Kodandaraman' and 'Kanchi' Valangum Perumal'.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=VjsfAAAAMAAJ&q=Kodandaraman&dq=Kodandaraman&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjY27i-trXZAhUDGuwKHbQpCgcQ6AEIXTAH|title=Tamil Coins: A Study|last=N\u0101kac\u0101mi|first=Ir\u0101maccantiran\u0332|last2=Nagaswamy|first2=R.|date=1981|publisher=Institute of Epigraphy, Tamilnadu State Department of Archaeology|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=102|language=en}}</ref> Apart from these, 'Ellamthalaiyanam' was seen on coins which had the standing king on one side and the fish on the other. 'Samarakolahalam' and 'Bhuvanekaviram' were found on the coins having a [[Garuda]], 'Konerirayan' on coins having a bull and 'Kaliyugaraman' on coins that depict a pair of feet.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=lNx31XT747wC&pg=PA164&dq=pandya+Konerirayan&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbkaSTt7XZAhWB2qQKHSzcB8wQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=pandya%20Konerirayan&f=false|title=South Indian Coins|last=Desikachari|first=T.|date=1991|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=|isbn=9788120601550|location=|pages=164|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Pearl fishing===\n\nThe early historic Pandya country was famous for its supply of pearls. The ancient port of [[Korkai]], in present-day [[Thoothukudi district|Thoothukudi]], was the center of pearl trade. Written records from [[Classical antiquity|Graeco-Roman]] and Egyptian voyagers give details about the pearl fisheries off the [[Gulf of Mannar]]. [[Megasthenes]] reported about the pearl fisheries, indicating that the Pandyas derived great wealth from the pearl trade.<ref>Kulke and Rothermund, p99, p107</ref>\n\nConvicts were according to the ''[[Periplus of the Erythraean Sea]]'' used as pearl divers in [[Korkai]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=PXXsAAAAIAAJ&q=korkai+convicts&dq=korkai+convicts&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAgevMr5nZAhVIjSwKHZ70C9A4ChDoAQgyMAI|title=Tamil social history|last=Subrahmanian|first=N.|last2=Hikosaka|first2=Shu|last3=Samuel|first3=G. John|last4=Thiagarajan|first4=P.|last5=India)|first5=Institute of Asian Studies (Madras|date=1997|publisher=Institute of Asian Studies|language=en}}</ref> The ''Periplus'' even mentions that \"pearls inferior to the Indian sort are exported in great quantity from the marts of Apologas and Omana\".{{sfn|Venkata Subramanian|1988|p=55}}  [[File:Silk route.jpg|thumb|250px| [[Silk Road]] map showing ancient trade routes.]]The pearls from the Pandya country were also in demand in the kingdoms of north India.<ref>{{cite book | last = Iyengar | first = P.T. Srinivasa | title = History of the Tamils: From the Earliest Times to 600 AD | page = 22 | publisher = Asian Educational Services | year = 2001 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ERq-OCn2cloC&pg=PA189&ots=Fp5loyJrzM&dq=musiri+pandyas&sig=aNcEToGTkngMTlXNVQAYgL95TTc#PPA22,M1 | accessdate = 2007-07-15}}</ref> Literary references of the pearl fishing mention how the fishermen, who dive into the sea, avoid attacks from sharks, bring up the right-whorled chank and blow on the sounding shell.<ref>{{cite book | title = A Political and General History of the District of Tinnevelly | last = Caldwell | first = Robert | year = 1881 | page = 20 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ERq-OCn2cloC&pg=PA189&ots=Fp5loyJrzM&dq=musiri+pandyas&sig=aNcEToGTkngMTlXNVQAYgL95TTc#PPA297,M1 | accessdate = 2005-07-15}}</ref>\n\n===Religion===\nThe Pandya country was home to a number of renowned temples including [[Meenakshi Temple]] in [[Madurai]]. After the revival of the Pandya power by [[Kadungon]], the Shaivite [[nayanars]] and the Vaishnavite [[alvars]] of the Bhakti movement rose to prominence.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nIt is known that the Pandya rulers followed [[Jainism]] for a short period of time in history.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Architecture==\n{{further|Pandyan art and architecture}}\n[[File:Tirunelveli Nellaiappar Temple 1.jpg|250px|thumb|upright| The [[Gopuram]] of [[Nellaiappar Temple]] ]]Rock cut and structural temples were a significant part of the Pandya architecture. The [[Vimana (architectural feature)|vimana]] and [[mandapa]] are some of the features of the Pandya temples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?hl=no&id=H821AAAAIAAJ&dq=pandyan+architecture&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=vimana|title=Studies in Indian history and culture: volume presented to Dr. P. B. Desai ... on the occasion of his completing sixty years|last=Desai|first=Pandurang Bhimarao|date=1971|publisher=Prof. P. B. Desai Felicitation Committee, Karnatak University; [for copies write to the printer: K. E. B's Print. Press]|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=125|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGroups of small temples are seen at [[Tiruchirappalli district]] of Tamil Nadu. The Shiva temples have a [[Nandi (bull)|Nandi bull]] sculpture in front of the ''maha mandapa''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=TlvqAAAAMAAJ&q=nandi+statue+pandya&dq=nandi+statue+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjfwoLPr7XZAhXDzqQKHdiBCWwQ6AEIRDAE|title=Rock-cut temple styles: early Pandya art and the Ellora shrines|last=Rajan|first=K. V. Soundara|date=1998-03-01|publisher=Somaiya Publications|year=|isbn=9788170392187|location=|pages=58|language=en}}</ref> In the later stages of Pandyas rule, finely sculptured idols, [[gopuram]]s on the [[Vimana (architectural feature)|vimanas]] were developed. Gopurams are the rectangular entrance and portals of the temples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=vyXxEX5PQH8C&pg=PA337&dq=gopuram+pandya+temple&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjDxcGBsbXZAhWJGuwKHefjApMQ6AEIODAC#v=onepage&q=gopuram%20pandya%20temple&f=false|title=Ornament in Indian Architecture|last=Allen|first=Margaret Prosser|date=1991|publisher=University of Delaware Press|year=|isbn=9780874133998|location=|pages=350|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Meenakshi Amman Temple]] in Madurai and [[Nellaiappar Temple]] in [[Tirunelveli]] were built during the reign of the Pandyas.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.no/books?id=6HAeAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA470&dq=meenakshi+temple+pandya&hl=no&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjr0v67sbXZAhVOCewKHVTZA-kQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=meenakshi%20temple%20pandya&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of India|last=Mansingh|first=Surjit|date=2006-05-09|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|year=|isbn=9780810865020|location=|pages=430|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-1-of-2}}\n* [[Pandyan Civil War (1169\u20131177)]]\n* [[History of Tamil Nadu]]\n* [[History of Kerala]]\n* [[Economy of ancient Tamil country]]\n* [[Industry in ancient Tamil country]]\n{{Col-2-of-2}}\n* [[Tamilakam]]\n* [[Tammuzh]]\n* [[List of Tamil monarchs]]\n* [[Indo-Roman relations]]\n* [[Indo-Roman trade relations]]\n* [[Indian maritime history]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{commons category|Pandyan Dynasty}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Balambal |first=V. |title=Studies in the History of the Sangam Age |date=1998 |publisher=Kalinga Publications |isbn=978-81-85163-87-1 }}\n* Carswell, John. 1991. \"The Port of Mantai, Sri Lanka.\" ''RAI'', pp.&nbsp;197\u2013203.\n* {{cite book |last=Curtin |first=Philip D. |title=Cross-Cultural Trade in World History |year=1984 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-26931-5}}\n* Hill, John E. 2004. ''The Peoples of the West from the Weil\u00fce'' \u9b4f\u7565 ''by Yu Huan'' \u9b5a\u8c62'': A Third Century Chinese Account Composed between 239 and 265 CE.'' [http://depts.washington.edu/silkroad/texts/weilue/weilue.html Draft annotated English translation.]\n* {{cite book |last=Holl |first=Augustin |title=Ethnoarchaeology of Shuwa-Arab Settlements |year=2003 |publisher=Lexington Books |isbn=978-0-7391-0407-1}}\n* {{cite book | last = Husaini| first = A.Q. | title = History of The Pandya Country | year = 1972 }}\n* {{cite book | first= John  | last= Keay | authorlink= | author2= | origyear = 2001| year= 2000| title= India: A hi