{"title_page": "List of asteroid close approaches to Earth", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[Image:2004fs56992main 2004.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.3|Trajectory of [[2004 FH]] in the Earth\u2013Moon system]]\n[[File:Pa8radar.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.3|[[Goldstone Deep Space Communications Complex|Goldstone]] [[radar astronomy|radar]] images of asteroid {{mpl|2007 PA|8}}'s Earth flyby in 2012]]\n\nThis is a list of examples where an [[asteroid]] or [[meteoroid]] travels close to the Earth. Some are regarded as [[potentially hazardous object]]s if they are estimated to be large enough to cause regional devastation.\n\n[[Near-Earth object]] detection technology greatly improved about 1998, so objects being detected as of 2004 could have been missed only a decade earlier due to a lack of dedicated near-Earth [[astronomical survey]]s. As sky surveys improve, smaller and smaller asteroids are regularly being discovered. The small near-Earth asteroids {{mpl|2008 TC|3}}, [[2014 AA]], [[2018 LA]] and [[2019 MO]] are the only four asteroids discovered before impacting into Earth (see [[asteroid impact prediction]]). Scientists estimate that several dozen asteroids in the {{convert|6-12|m|abbr=on}} size range fly by Earth at a distance [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2013|closer than the moon every year]], but only a fraction of these are actually detected.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?release=2014-052 |title=Responding to Potential Asteroid Redirect Mission Targets |access-date=2014-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226020619/http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/news/news.php?release=2014-052 |archive-date=2014-02-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20180614c\">{{cite news |last=Chang |first=Kenneth |title=Asteroids and Adversaries: Challenging What NASA Knows About Space Rocks - Relevant Comments |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/14/science/asteroids-nasa-nathan-myhrvold.html#permid=27500228:27506217 |date=June 14, 2018 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=July 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180622170339/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/14/science/asteroids-nasa-nathan-myhrvold.html#permid=27500228:27506217 |archive-date=June 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Timeline of approaches within one lunar distance==\nThe average distance to the Moon (or [[Lunar distance (astronomy)|lunar distance (LD)]]) is about {{convert|384400|km|abbr=on}}, which is around 30 times the diameter of the Earth.<ref name=\"dist-moon\">{{cite web |author=NASA Staff |title=Solar System Exploration: Planets: Earth's Moon: Facts & Figures |url=http://solarsystem.nasa.gov/planets/profile.cfm?Display=Facts&Object=Moon |date=10 May 2011 |publisher=NASA |accessdate=6 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140210103759/http://solarsystem.nasa.gov/planets/profile.cfm?Object=Moon&Display=Facts |archive-date=10 February 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Below are lists of close approaches less than one LD for a given year. (See also [[Near-Earth object#Near-Earth asteroids|near-Earth asteroids]] published by the [[International Astronomical Union]]<ref group=\"note\">: [http://www.iau.org/public/nea/ \"Near Earth Asteroids (NEAs): A Chronology of Milestones\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302015203/http://iau.org/public/nea |date=2013-03-02 }}.</ref> and [http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/ca NEO Earth Close Approaches].)\n\n{|\n|{{Bar graph\n| title       = Known asteroids passing <1 [[Lunar distance (astronomy)|LD]] from Earth\n| float       = center\n| data_max    = 100\n| bar_width   = 15\n| width_units = em\n| label_type  = year\n| data_type   = discovered on [[Opposition (astronomy)|opposition]]\n| label1 = 2001\n| data1 = 1\n| label2 = 2002\n| data2 = 2\n| label3= 2003\n| data3 = 5\n| label4= 2004\n| data4 = 10\n| label5 = 2005\n| data5 = 6\n| label6 = 2006\n| data6 = 12\n| label7 = 2007\n| data7 = 15\n| label8 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2008|2008]]\n| data8 = 20\n| label9 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2009|2009]]\n| data9 = 19\n| label10 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2010|2010]]\n| data10 = 22\n| label11 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2011|2011]]\n| data11 = 27\n| label12 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2012|2012]]\n| data12 = 22\n| label13 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2013|2013]]\n| data13 = 23\n| label14 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2014|2014]]\n| data14 = 32\n| label15 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2015|2015]]\n| data15 = 27\n| label16 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2016|2016]]\n| data16 = 60\n| label17 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2017|2017]]\n| data17 = 56\n| label18 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2018|2018]]\n| data18 = 91\n| label19 = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2019|2019]]\n| data19 = 17\n| col2_data_type= discovered later\n| col2_data_max = 100\n| col2_data1 = 1\n| col2_data2 = 0\n| col2_data3 = 0\n| col2_data4 = 0\n| col2_data5 = 0\n| col2_data6 = 0\n| col2_data7 = 0\n| col2_data8 = 0\n| col2_data9 = 0\n| col2_data10 = 0\n| col2_data11 = 0\n| col2_data12 = 0\n| col2_data13 = 0\n| col2_data14 = 0\n| col2_data15 = 0\n| col2_data16 = 0\n| col2_data17 = 0\n| col2_data18 = 0\n| col2_data19 = 0\n| col3_data_type = discovered prior\n| col3_data_max = 100\n| col3_data1 = 0\n| col3_data2 = 0\n| col3_data3 = 0\n| col3_data4 = 0\n| col3_data5 = 0\n| col3_data6 = 0\n| col3_data7 = 1\n| col3_data8 = 0\n| col3_data9 = 0\n| col3_data10 = 0\n| col3_data11 = 3\n| col3_data12 = 0\n| col3_data13 = 1\n| col3_data14 = 0\n| col3_data15 = 0\n| col3_data16 = 0\n| col3_data17 = 1\n| col3_data18 = 2\n| col3_data19 = 0\n}}\n|{{ #invoke:Chart | bar chart\n| height = 400\n| width = 400\n| stack = 1\n<!--         2013 2014 2015 2016 2017 2018 2019 -->\n| group 1 =    0 :  0 :  0 :  0 :  1 :  2 :  0\n| group 2 =    1 :  0 :  0 :  0 :  0 :  0 :  0\n| group 3 =    0 :  1 :  1 :  0 :  1 :  0 :  4\n| group 4 =    9 :  8 :  6 : 17 : 23 : 26 : 20\n| group 5 =    2 :  5 :  3 :  5 :  6 : 11 : 11\n| group 6 =   12 : 18 : 17 : 38 : 26 : 54 : 47\n| group names = Discovered > 1 year in advance\n              : Discovered > 7 weeks in advance\n              : Discovered > 1 week in advance\n              : Discovered up to 1 week in advance\n              : < 24 hours' warning\n              : No warning\n| colors = blue : turquoise : green : gray : yellow : red\n| x legends = [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2013|2013]]\n            : [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2014|2014]]\n            : [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2015|2015]]\n            : [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2016|2016]]\n            : [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2017|2017]]\n            : [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2018|2018]]\n            : [[List of asteroid close approaches to Earth in 2019|2019]]\n}}\n|}\n===Closest known per year===\n[[File:Geostationaryjava3Dsideview.gif|thumb|Satellites in [[geostationary orbit]]]]\nFrom the list in the first section, these are the closest-known asteroids per year that approach [[Earth]] within one [[lunar distance (astronomy)|lunar distance]]. More than one asteroid per year may be listed if its geocentric distance<ref group=\"note\">Distance from the center of Earth to the center of the object. See the [[NASA]]/[[JPL]] Solar System Dynamics Glossary: [http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/?glossary&term=geocentric Geocentric] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214203225/http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/?glossary&term=geocentric |date=2013-02-14 }}. Earth has a [[Earth radius|radius]] of approximately 6,400 km.</ref> is within a tenth of the lunar distance, or 0.10 LD. For comparison, since a satellite in a [[geostationary orbit]] has an [[altitude]] of about {{convert|36000|km|abbr=on}}, then its geocentric distance is 0.11 LD (approximately three times the width of the Earth).\n\nThe table shows that the years 2016 and 2017 had a total of 13 such close encounters that are known. Of these, eight were undetected until after they'd happened and only one was detected with more than 24 hours' notice. 2018 has fared better so far, with six out of the eight known close encounters being detected beforehand, albeit with less than 24 hours' notice in most cases.\n\nThis list does not include any of the [[List of bolides|hundreds of objects that collided with Earth]], which were not discovered in advance, but were recorded by sensors designed to detect detonation of nuclear devices. Of the objects so detected, 78 had an impact energy greater than that of a 1-kiloton device (equivalent to 1000 tons of TNT), including 11 which had an impact energy greater than that of a 10-kiloton device i.e. comparable to the atomic bombs used in the [[Second World War]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/fireballs | title=Fireballs | access-date=2018-07-23 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314153125/https://cneos.jpl.nasa.gov/fireballs | archive-date=2017-03-14 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{color box|#ff9999}} Rows highlighted red indicate objects which were not discovered until after closest approach\n\n{{color box|#ffff99}} Rows highlighted yellow indicate objects discovered less than 24 hours before closest approach\n\n{{color box|#99ff99}} Rows highlighted green indicate objects discovered more than one week before closest approach\n\n{{color box|#79d8ff}} Rows highlighted blue indicate objects discovered more than one year before closest approach, i.e. objects successfully cataloged on a previous orbit, rather than being detected during final approach.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Year !! Date of<br/>closest approach !! width= 120 |Date<br/>disco