10cerven\u00e1 hora ([[Czechoslovakia]]), one of the stations of the [[European Fireball Network]]. The bright track on the left is the [[Moon]].]]\n{{main article|Earth-grazing fireball}}\n\nObjects which enter and then leave [[Atmosphere of Earth|Earth's atmosphere]], the so-called '[[Earth-grazing fireball|Earth-grazers]]', are a distinct phenomenon, in as much as entering the lower atmosphere can constitute an [[impact event]] rather than a close pass. Earth grazer can also be short for a body that \"grazes\" the orbit of the Earth, in a different context.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Altitude<br>(km) !! Size (m)<br>(approximate) !! Mass (kg)<br>(approximate) !! Date of<br>closest approach !! Object !! Note !! Ref.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 0 ||colspan=6 align=\"center\"|mean [[sea level]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 8.8 ||colspan=6 align=\"center\"|[[Mount Everest]] (height)\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 58 ||align=\"center\"| 5 ||align=\"center\"| 10<sup>5</sup>\u201310<sup>6</sup> || August 10, 1972 || [[1972 Great Daylight Fireball]] above the United States and Canada || First scientifically observed ||<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Ceplecha\n | first = Z.\n | title = Earth-grazing daylight fireball of August 10, 1972\n | journal = Astronomy and Astrophysics\n | volume = 283\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 287\u2013288\n | date = March 1994\n | bibcode = 1994A&A...283..287C\n | issn = 0004-6361\n | doi =\n }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 71.4 ||align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"| 100 || March 29, 2006 || 2006 Earth-grazing Fireball above Japan || || \n<ref name=\"EPSC\">{{cite conference\n | first = Abe\n | last = S.\n | first2 = Borovi\u010dka\n | last2 = J.\n | first3 = Spurn\u00fd\n | last3 = P.\n | first4 = Koten\n | last4 = P.\n | first5 = Ceplecha\n | last5 = Z.\n | author6 = Meteor Network Team in Japan\n | title = Earth-grazing fireball on March 29, 2006\n | booktitle = European Planetary Science Congress 2006\n | pages = 486\n | date = 18\u201322 September 2006\n 