 |title=(214869) 2007 PA8 Goldstone Radar Observations Planning |last=Benner |first=Lance A. M |work=Asteroid Radar Research |publisher=JPL/California Institute of Technology |accessdate=14 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130216031533/http://echo.jpl.nasa.gov/asteroids/2007PA8/2007PA8_planning.html |archive-date=16 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> || {{JPL+CAD|214869}}\n|-\n|0.046332||align=\"center\"|6,900,000 ||align=\"center\"| 5400 || December 12, 2012 || [[4179 Toutatis]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universetoday.com/98923/two-asteroids-will-buzz-past-earth-on-december-11/#more-98923 |title=Two Asteroids Will Buzz Past Earth on December 11 |last=Atkinson |first=Nancy |publisher=[[Universe Today]] |date=11 December 2012 |accessdate=12 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130326091952/http://www.universetoday.com/98923/two-asteroids-will-buzz-past-earth-on-december-11/#more-98923 |archive-date=26 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> || {{JPL+CAD|4179}}\n|}\n\n<small>Asteroids with large uncertainty regions are not included.</small>\n\n<small>* Asteroid approach did not occur during an observed apparition. Passage is calculated by integrating the [[equations of motion]].</small>\n\n<small>** Only the nominal ([[Curve fitting|best-fit]]) orbit shows a passage this close. The uncertainty region is still somewhat large due to a short observation arc.</small>\n\n==Predicted encounters==\n\nIncomplete list of asteroids larger than about {{convert|50|m|abbr=on}} predicted to pass close to Earth (see also [[asteroid impact prediction]] and [[Sentry (monitoring system)]]):<ref name=\"NASA-close-approach\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/PHACloseApp.html |title=PHA Close Approaches To The Earth |publisher=International Astronomical Union/Minor Planet Center |accessdate=14 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104144458/http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/PHACloseApp.html |archive-date=4 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Nominal<br/>geocentric<br/>distance ([[astronomical unit|AU]]) !! Nominal<br/>geocentric<br/>distance (km) !! Size (m)<br/>(estimated) !! Date of<br/>closest approach !! Object !! JPL-Ref\n|-\n|0.000256||align=\"center\"| 38,300 ||align=\"center\"| 325 || April 13, 2029 || [[99942 Apophis]] || {{JPL+CAD|99942}}\n|-\n|0.000670||align=\"center\"| 100,200 ||align=\"center\"| 75\u2013170 || October 19, 2129 || {{mpl|2007 UW|1}} || {{JPL+CAD|2007+UW1}}\n|-\n|0.000721||align=\"center\"| 107,800 ||align=\"center\"| 50\u2013120 || April 8, 2041 || {{mpl|2012 UE|34}} || {{JPL+CAD|2012+UE34}}\n|-\n|0.001572||align=\"center\"| 235,200 ||align=\"center\"| 170\u2013370 || January 2, 2101 || {{mpl|(456938) 2007 YV|56}} || {{JPL+CAD|456938}}\n|-\n|0.001585||align=\"center\"| 237,000 ||align=\"center\"| 360\u00b140 || November 8, 2075 || {{mpl|(308635) 2005 YU|55}} || {{JPL+CAD|308635}}\n|-\n|0.001629||align=\"center\"| 243,700 ||align=\"center\"| 370\u2013840 || December 1, 2140 || {{mpl|(153201) 2000 WO|107}} || {{JPL+CAD|153201}}\n|-\n|0.001635<sup>**</sup>||align=\"center\"| 244,600 ||align=\"center\"| 190\u2013420 || October 26, 2087 || {{mpl|2011 WL|2}} || {{JPL+CAD|2011+WL2}}\n|-\n|0.001663||align=\"center\"| 248,800 ||align=\"center\"| 700\u20131500 || June 26, 2028 || {{mpl|(153814) 2001 WN|5}} || {{JPL+CAD|153814}}\n|-\n|0.001980||align=\"center\"| 296,200 ||align=\"center\"| 170\u2013370 || January 22, 2148 || {{mpl|(85640) 1998 OX|4}} || {{JPL+CAD|85640}}\n|-\n|0.002222||align=\"center\"| 332,500 ||align=\"center\"| 190\u2013250 || May 28, 2065 || {{mpl|2005 WY|55}} || {{JPL+CAD|2005+WY55}}\n|-\n|0.002241||align=\"center\"| 335,200 ||align=\"center\"| 75\u2013170 || March 23, 2146 || {{mp|2009 DO|111}} || {{JPL+CAD|2009+DO111}}\n|-bgcolor=#e6e6e6\n|0.00257|| align=\"center\"| 384,400 || colspan=4 align=\"center\"| for comparison, this is the [[Lunar distance (astronomy)|average distance to the Moon]]<ref name=\"dist-moon\"/>\n|}\n\nA list of predicted NEO approaches at larger distances is maintained as a database by the NASA Near Earth Object Program.<ref>NASA, Near Earth Object Program, database [http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/cgi-bin/neo_ca NEO Earth Close-Approaches Between 1900 A.D. and 2200 A.D. limited to encounters with reasonably low uncertainty] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217213200/http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/cgi-bin/neo_ca |date=2013-02-17 }} (accessed 20 Sept. 2013)</ref>\n\n<small>** Only the nominal ([[Curve fitting|best-fit]]) orbit shows a passage this close. The uncertainty region is still somewhat large due to a short observation arc.</small>\n\n==Earth grazers==\n\n[[File:Earth-grazing meteoroid, 13 October 1990 (2).jpg|thumb|All-sky photo with the [[Earth-grazing meteoroid of 13 October 1990]] (the light track across the picture going from the south to the north) taken at \u010cerven\u00e1 hora ([[Czechoslovakia]]), one of the stations of the [[European Fireball Network]]. The bright track on the left is the [[Moon]].]]\n{{main article|Earth-grazing fireball}}\n\nObjects which enter and then leave [[Atmosphere of Earth|Earth's atmosphere]], the so-called '[[Earth-grazing fireball|Earth-grazers]]', are a distinct phenomenon, in as much as entering the lower atmosphere can constitute an [[impact event]] rather than a close pass. Earth grazer can also be short for a body that \"grazes\" the orbit of the Earth, in a different context.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Altitude<br>(km) !! Size (m)<br>(approximate) !! Mass (kg)<br>(approximate) !! Date of<br>closest approach !! Object !! Note !! Ref.\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 0 ||colspan=6 align=\"center\"|mean [[sea level]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 8.8 ||colspan=6 align=\"center\"|[[Mount Everest]] (height)\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 58 ||align=\"center\"| 5 ||align=\"center\"| 10<sup>5</sup>\u201310<sup>6</sup> || August 10, 1972 || [[1972 Great Daylight Fireball]] above the United States and Canada || First scientifically observed ||<ref>{{cite journal\n | last = Ceplecha\n | first = Z.\n | title = Earth-grazing daylight fireball of August 10, 1972\n | journal = Astronomy and Astrophysics\n | volume = 283\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 287\u2013288\n | date = March 1994\n | bibcode = 1994A&A...283..287C\n | issn = 0004-6361\n | doi =\n }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 71.4 ||align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"| 100 || March 29, 2006 || 2006 Earth-grazing Fireball above Japan || || \n<ref name=\"EPSC\">{{cite conference\n | first = Abe\n | last = S.\n | first2 = Borovi\u010dka\n | last2 = J.\n | first3 = Spurn\u00fd\n | last3 = P.\n | first4 = Koten\n | last4 = P.\n | first5 = Ceplecha\n | last5 = Z.\n | author6 = Meteor Network Team in Japan\n | title = Earth-grazing fireball on March 29, 2006\n | booktitle = European Planetary Science Congress 2006\n | pages = 486\n | date = 18\u201322 September 2006\n | location = Berlin\n | url = http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/full/conf/epsc./2006//0000486.001.html\n | bibcode = 2006epsc.conf..486A\n | accessdate = 2015-03-14\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190528072728/http://articles.adsabs.harvard.edu/full/conf/epsc./2006//0000486.001.html\n | archive-date = 28 May 2019\n | url-status = live\n }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 98.7 ||align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"| 44 || October 13, 1990 || [[Earth-grazing meteoroid of 13 October 1990|1990 Earth-grazing Fireball]] above Czechoslovakia and Poland || First captured from 2 distant locations, which enabled computing its orbit by geometrical methods ||<ref name=\"AA\">{{cite journal\n | last = Borovi\u010dka\n | first = J.\n | authorlink =\n | last2 = Ceplecha\n | first2 = Z.\n | title = Earth-grazing fireball of October 13, 1990\n | journal = Astronomy and Astrophysics\n | volume = 257\n | issue = 1\n | pages = 323\u2013328\n | date = April 1992\n | bibcode = 1992A&A...257..323B\n | issn = 0004-6361\n | doi =\n }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"| ||align=\"center\"| || August 7, 2007 || 2007 Earth-grazing Fireball || Its pre-encounter orbit belonged to the rare [[Aten asteroid|Aten type]] ||<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Spurn\u00fd\n | first = P.\n | last2 = Borovi\u010dka\n | first2 = J.\n | last3 = Ceplecha\n | first3 = Z.\n | last4 = Shrben\u00fd\n | first4 = L.\n | title = Precise Multi-Instrument Data on 45 Fireballs Recorded over Central Europe in the Period 2006-2008\n | volume = 1405\n | pages = 8217\n | work = Asteroids, Comets, Meteors 2008 held July 14\u201318, 2008 in Baltimore, Maryland\n | year = 2008\n | url = http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/acm2008/pdf/8217.pdf\n | bibcode = 2008LPICo1405.8217S\n | accessdate = 2015-03-14\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303221050/http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/acm2008/pdf/8217.pdf\n | archive-date = 2016-03-03\n | url-status = live\n }}</ref>\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| 100 || colspan=6 align=\"center\"|[[K\u00e1rm\u00e1n line]]\n|}\n\n==Animations==\n[[File:Asteroids-KnownNearEarthObjects-Animation-UpTo20180101.gif|thumb|left|600px|<center>Known [[near-Earth object]]s \u2013 as of January 2018<br>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vfvo-Ujb_qk Video (0:55; July 23, 2018)]</center>]]\n<!---Here is a simulated animation of the course of [[2015 TB145]], a NEO, during close approach to the Earth--->\n{| width=400\n|[[File:Asteroid flyby 2015 TB145.gif|thumb|475px|<center>Animation of the [[2015 TB145]] ([[Near-Earth object|NEO]]) flyby, as seen from the center of the [[Earth]], with hourly trace circles along the path of motion</center>]]\n|}\n\n==Overview==\n[[Image:Potentially Hazardous Asteroids 2013.png|thumb|left|550px|Plot of orbits of known Potentially Hazardous Asteroids (size over {{convert|460|ft|order=flip|disp=sqbr|abbr=unit}} and passing within {{convert|4.7|e6mi|e6km|order=flip|abbr=unit|disp=sqbr}} of Earth's orbit) as of early 2013 ([[:File:PIA17041-Orbits-PotentiallyHazardousAsteroids-Early2013.jpg|alternate image]])]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20141231154154/http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/risk/ Sentry Risk Table] \u2014 [[Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]\n*[http://www.minorplanetcenter.net/iau/lists/PHACloseApp.html \"PHA Close Approaches To The Earth\"] \u2014 [[Minor Planet Center]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140307125729/http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/ca/ \"NEO Earth Close Approaches\"] \u2014 NASA/JPL's Near-Earth Object Program Office\n*[http://neo.jpl.nasa.gov/cgi-bin/neo_ca?type=NEO&hmax=22&sort=dist&sdir=ASC&tlim=all&dmax=5LD&max_rows=20&action=Display+Table&show=1 \"NEO Earth Close-Approaches\" (Between 1900 A.D. and 2200 A.D., NEOs with H <=22, nominal distance within 5 LD)] \u2014 NASA/JPL's Near-Earth Object Program Office\n*[http://www.iau.org/public/nea/ \"Near Earth Asteroids (NEAs): A Chronology of Milestones\"] \u2014 International Astronomical Union\n*[http://newton.dm.unipi.it/neodys/ NEODyS-2] \u2014 Near Earth Objects Dynamic Site sponsored by [[ESA]]\n*[http://www.brera.mi.astro.it/sormano/teca.html TECA Table of asteroids next close approaches to the Earth] \u2014 Sormano Astronomical Observatory\n*[http://www.brera.mi.astro.it/sormano/sael.html SAEL Small Asteroids Encounter List] \u2014 Sormano Astronomical Observatory\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151103035053/http://earn.dlr.de/ E.A.R.N.] \u2014 European Asteroid Research Node\n*[http://andrew-lowe.ca/pha-soon.htm Upcoming Close Approaches (< 0.10 AU) of NEOs to the Inner Planets] - Andrew Lowe using Solex 11\n*[http://www.hohmanntransfer.com/ Earth's Busy Neighborhood] \u2014 HohmannTransfer\n*{{APOD |date=2 March 2009 |title=Earthgrazer: The Great Daylight Fireball of 1972}}\n\n{{Asteroids}}\n{{Modern impact events}}\n{{Planetary defense}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of asteroids| ]]\n[[Category:Near-Earth asteroids]]\n[[Category:Planetary defense]]\n", "name_user": "AlanM1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eClosest known per year:LinkA106fgF", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_asteroid_close_approaches_to_Earth"}
{"title_page": "Gordon Matta-Clark", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n | name          = Gordon Matta-Clark\n | image         = Opening the doors of Food.jpg\n | imagesize     = \n | caption       = 'Opening the doors of Food' (1971). Matta-Clark (right). \n | occupation    = Artist\n | birth_name    = Gordon Roberto Echaurren Matta\n | birth_date    = {{Birth date|1943|6|22|mf=yes}}\n | birth_place   = [[New York, New York]], U.S. \n | death_date    = {{death date and age |1978|8|27|1943|6|22|mf=yes}}\n | death_place   = [[New York, New York]], U.S. \n | spouse        = Jane Crawford (1977-1978; his death)\n | nationality   = [[United States|American]]}}\n\n'''Gordon Matta-Clark''' (born '''Gordon Roberto Echaurren Matta'''; June 22, 1943<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Arh7W3v0uVAC|title=Object to Be Destroyed: The Work of Gordon Matta-Clark|last=Lee|first=Pamela M.|page=3|year=2001|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|isbn=978-0-262-62156-4}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 August 27, 1978) was an [[United States|American]] artist best known for his site-specific artworks he made in the 1970s.\n\n==Life and work==\nMatta-Clark's parents were artists: Anne Clark, an American artist, and [[Roberto Matta]], a [[Chilean people|Chilean]] Surrealist painter, of [[Basque people|Basque]], [[French people|French]] and [[Spanish people|Spanish]] descent. He was the godson of [[Marcel Duchamp]]'s wife, [[Teeny Duchamp|Teeny]].<ref>[https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/gordon-matta-clark Gordon Matta-Clark Biography], [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]]; accessed 2017-07-10</ref> His twin brother Sebastian, also an artist, committed suicide in 1976.<ref>[http://www.artnet.com/Magazine/FEATURES/smyth/smyth6-4-04.asp Profile], artnet.com; retrieved October 23, 2009</ref>\n\nHe studied [[architecture]] at [[Cornell University]] from 1962 to 1968, including a year at the [[Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]] in Paris, where he studied French literature. In 1971, he changed his name to Gordon Matta-Clark, adopting his mother's last name.<ref>[http://museum.cornell.edu/exhibitions/cuts-video-works-gordon-matta-clark Profile], museum.cornell.edu; accessed July 10, 2017.</ref> He did not practice as a conventional architect; he worked on what he referred to as \"Anarchitecture\".<ref name=GMCW>{{Cite journal|title=Gordon Matta-Clark at the Whitney|author=William Hanley |publisher=ARTINFO|date=April 11, 2007|url=http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/24688/gordon-matta-clark-at-the-whitney|accessdate=2008-04-21}}</ref> At the time of Matta-Clark's tenure there, Cornell's architecture program was guided in part by [[Colin Rowe]],<ref>[http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/1996/03/festschrift-honor-architecture-scholar-colin-rowe Cornell Festschrift honors Colin Rowe, one of architecture's most influential scholars] ''Cornell Chronicle'', 1996-03-2; accessed 2015-07-28</ref> a preeminent architectural theorist of modernism.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Petit|editor-first=Emmanuel|title=Reckoning with Colin Rowe: Ten Architects Take Position|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nMatta-Clark used a number of media to document his work, including film, video, and photography. His work includes performance and recycling pieces, space and texture works, and his \"building cuts\". He also used puns and other word games as a way to re-conceptualize preconditioned roles and relationships (of everything, from people to architecture). {{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn February, 1969, the \"[[Earth Art]]\" show, curated by [[Willoughby Sharp]] at the invitation of Tom Leavitt, was realized at Andrew Dickson White Museum of Art, [[Cornell University]]. Matta-Clark, who lived in Ithaca at the time, was invited by Willoughby Sharp to help the artists in \"[[Earth Art]]\" with the on-site execution of their works for the exhibition. Sharp then encouraged Gordon Matta-Clark to move to New York City where Sharp continued to introduce him to members of the New York art world. Matta-Clark's work, ''Museum,'' at [[Klaus Kertess]]' [[Bykert Gallery]], was listed and illustrated on pages 4\u20135 of ''Avalanche'' 1, Fall 1970.\n\nIn 1971 Matta-Clark, [[Carol Goodden]], and [[Tina Girouard]] co-founded [[FOOD]], a restaurant in Manhattan's [[SoHo, New York| Soho]] neighborhood; managed and staffed by artists.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Waxman|first=Lori|title=The Banquet Years: FOOD, A SoHo Restaurant|journal=Gastronomica: The Journal of Food and Culture|date=2008|volume=8|issue=4|pages=24\u201333|doi=10.1525/gfc.2008.8.4.24}}</ref> The restaurant turned dining into an event with an open kitchen and exotic ingredients that celebrated cooking. The activities at FOOD helped delineate how the art community defined itself in downtown Manhattan.<ref name=\"GMCW\"/> The first of its kind in SoHo, Food became well known among artists and was a central meeting-place for groups such as the [[Philip Glass Ensemble]], [[Mabou Mines]], and the dancers of [[Grand Union (dance group)|Grand Union]]. He ran FOOD until 1973.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Gordon Matta-Clark|author=Steven Stern|magazine=Frieze Magazine|date=September 2007|url=https://frieze.com/article/gordon-matta-clark-0|accessdate=2017-07-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970s and in the context of his artistic community surrounding FOOD, Matta-Clark developed the idea of \"anarchitecture\" - a conflation of the words anarchy and architecture - to suggest an interest in voids, gaps, and left-over spaces.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Rocking the Foundation|author=Jeff Rian|magazine=Frieze Magazine|date=June 1993|url=https://frieze.com/article/rocking-foundation|accessdate=2017-07-10}}</ref> With his project Fake Estates, Matta-Clark addressed these issues of non-sites by purchasing at auction 15 leftover and unusably small slivers of land in Queens and Staten Island, [[New York (state)|New York]], for $25\u2013$75 a plot. He documented them through photographs, maps, bureaucratic records and deeds, and spoke and wrote about them - but was not able to occupy these residual elements of zoning irregularities in any other way.<ref>{{cite book| editor-last=Kastner| editor-first=Jeffrey|editor2-last=Najafi|editor2-first=Sina|editor3-last=Richard|editor3-first=Frances|title=Odd Lots: Revisiting Gordon Matta-Clark's Fake Estates|publisher=Cabinet Books|year=2005|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=Odd Lots: Revisiting Gordon Matta-Clark's Fake Estates| publisher=Cabinet| date=2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, he performed a literal [[deconstruction]], by removing the facade of a condemned house along the [[Love Canal]], and moving the resulting walls to [[Artpark]], in his work ''Bingo''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Bingo Ninths''|format=video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OoUbs1-oSxI|accessdate=2008-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bingo|url=http://www.artfacts.net/index.php/pageType/exhibitionInfo/exhibition/15849/lang/2|accessdate=2008-10-26}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[Biennale de Paris]] in 1975, he made the piece titled Conical Intersect by cutting a large cone-shaped hole through two townhouses dating from the 17th century in the market district known as [[Les Halles]] which were to be knocked down in order to construct the then-controversial [[Centre Georges Pompidou]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Bruce|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: Conical Intersect|date=2011|publisher=Afterall Books|location=London}}</ref>\n\nFor his final major project, ''Circus or The Caribbean Orange'' (1978), Matta-Clark made circle cuts in the walls and floors of a townhouse next-door to the first [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]], building (237 East Ontario Street), thus altering the space entirely.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.artdaily.com/index.asp?int_sec=11&int_new=22966&int_modo=2|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: You Are the Measure|work=Artdaily|year=2008|accessdate=2011-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcachicago.org/information/history.php?page=ihist|title=History of the MCA|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|accessdate=2011-06-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725013043/http://www.mcachicago.org/information/history.php?page=ihist|archivedate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his 1978 project, the MCA presented two retrospectives of Matta-Clark's work, in 1985 and in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mcachicago.org/Exhibitions/2008/Gordon-Matta-Clark-You-Are-The-Measure|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: You Are the Measure|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|accessdate=2017-07-10}}</ref> The 2008 exhibition ''You Are the Measure'' included never-before-displayed archival material of his 1978 Chicago project. ''You Are the Measure'' traveled to the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York, and the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcachicago.org/media_uploads/releases/45b89Gordon.pdf|work=Press Release|date=2008-01-01|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: You Are the Measure|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|accessdate=2011-06-13}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nMatta-Clark died from [[pancreatic cancer]] on August 27, 1978, aged 35, in [[New York, New York]].<ref>[http://www.davidzwirner.com/artists/gordon-matta-clark/biography Profile], davidzwirner.com; accessed March 28, 2015.</ref> He was survived by his widow, Jane Crawford. The Gordon Matta-Clark Archive is housed at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], Montreal.<ref>[https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/370196 Gordon Matta-Clark Archive], cca.qc.ca; accessed 2015-07-29.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/03/arts/design/03matt.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 Profile], nytimes.com; accessed March 28, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Videography==\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=2169 ''Program One: Chinatown Voyeur'' (1971)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3495 ''Program Two'' (1971-1972)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13702 ''Tree Dance'' (1971)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13678 ''Open House'' (1972)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3791 ''Program Three'' (1971-1975)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13692 ''Fire Child'' (1971)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13841 ''Fresh Kill'' (1972)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13842 ''Day's End'' (1975)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=761 ''Food'' (1972)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3811 '' Program Five'' (1972-1976)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13843 ''Automation House'' (1972)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13844 ''Clockshower'' (1973)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13845 ''City Slivers'' (1976)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=1533 ''Program Four: Sauna View'' (1973)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=2925 ''Program Six'' (1974-1976)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13657 ''Splitting'' (1974)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13846 ''Bingo/Ninths'' (1974)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13847 ''Substrait (Underground Dailies)'' (1976)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=2359 ''Program Seven'' (1974-2005)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13637 ''Conical Intersect\" (1975)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=9797 ''Sous-Sols de Paris (Paris Underground)'' (1977-2005)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=12568 ''The Wall'' (1976-2007)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3313 ''Program Eight: Office Baroque'' (1977-2005)]\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n\n* [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/2715/out-of-the-box-price-rossi-stirling-matta-clark out of the box: price rossi stirling + matta-clark], [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]] (2003-2004)\n* [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/2686/absent-wall-recalling-gordon-matta-clarks-garbage-wall-1970 Absent Wall: Recalling Gordon Matta-Clark\u2019s Garbage Wall (1970)], [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]] (2004)\n* [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/66001/material-thinking-gordon-matta-clark-selected-by-yann-chateigne Material Thinking: Gordon Matta-Clark selected by Yann Chateign\u00e9], [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]] (2019)\n* [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/67324/rough-cuts-and-outtakes-gordon-matta-clark-selected-by-hila-peleg Rough Cuts and Outtakes: Gordon Matta-Clark selected by Hila Peleg], [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]] (2019-2020)\n* [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/events/71107/line-of-flight-gordon-matta-clark-selected-by-kitty-scott Line of Flight: Gordon Matta-Clark selected by Kitty Scott], [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], [[Montreal]] (2020)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MoMA artist|6636}}\n*[https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/370196 Gordon Matta-Clark archive], cca.qc.ca ([https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search?page=1&digigroup=370196 digitized items])\n*[http://www.davidzwirner.com/artists/4/press.htm Selected Press], DavidZwirner.com\n*[http://www.artnet.com/artist/11329/Gordon_Matta-Clark.html Profile], Artnet.com \n*[http://www.eai.org/artists/gordon-matta-clark/biography EAI: Gordon Matta-Clark Biography] and a list of [http://www.eai.org/artists/gordon-matta-clark/titles video works] by the artist\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matta-Clark, Gordon}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American people of Chilean descent]]\n[[Category:American conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:Deconstructivism]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Cornell University College of Architecture, Art, and Planning alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n | name          = Gordon Matta-Clark\n | image         = Opening the doors of Food.jpg\n | imagesize     = \n | caption       = 'Opening the doors of Food' (1971). Matta-Clark (right). \n | occupation    = Artist\n | birth_name    = Gordon Roberto Echaurren Matta\n | birth_date    = {{Birth date|1943|6|22|mf=yes}}\n | birth_place   = [[New York, New York]], U.S. \n | death_date    = {{death date and age |1978|8|27|1943|6|22|mf=yes}}\n | death_place   = [[New York, New York]], U.S. \n | spouse        = Jane Crawford (1977-1978; his death)\n | nationality   = [[United States|American]]}}\n\n'''Gordon Matta-Clark''' (born '''Gordon Roberto Echaurren Matta'''; June 22, 1943<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Arh7W3v0uVAC|title=Object to Be Destroyed: The Work of Gordon Matta-Clark|last=Lee|first=Pamela M.|page=3|year=2001|publisher=[[MIT Press]]|isbn=978-0-262-62156-4}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 August 27, 1978) was an [[United States|American]] artist best known for his site-specific artworks he made in the 1970s.\n\n==Life and work==\nMatta-Clark's parents were artists: Anne Clark, an American artist, and [[Roberto Matta]], a [[Chilean people|Chilean]] Surrealist painter, of [[Basque people|Basque]], [[French people|French]] and [[Spanish people|Spanish]] descent. He was the godson of [[Marcel Duchamp]]'s wife, [[Teeny Duchamp|Teeny]].<ref>[https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/gordon-matta-clark Gordon Matta-Clark Biography], [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum|Guggenheim Museum]]; accessed 2017-07-10</ref> His twin brother Sebastian, also an artist, committed suicide in 1976.<ref>[http://www.artnet.com/Magazine/FEATURES/smyth/smyth6-4-04.asp Profile], artnet.com; retrieved October 23, 2009</ref>\n\nHe studied [[architecture]] at [[Cornell University]] from 1962 to 1968, including a year at the [[Sorbonne University|Sorbonne]] in Paris, where he studied French literature. In 1971, he changed his name to Gordon Matta-Clark, adopting his mother's last name.<ref>[http://museum.cornell.edu/exhibitions/cuts-video-works-gordon-matta-clark Profile], museum.cornell.edu; accessed July 10, 2017.</ref> He did not practice as a conventional architect; he worked on what he referred to as \"Anarchitecture\".<ref name=GMCW>{{Cite journal|title=Gordon Matta-Clark at the Whitney|author=William Hanley |publisher=ARTINFO|date=April 11, 2007|url=http://www.artinfo.com/news/story/24688/gordon-matta-clark-at-the-whitney|accessdate=2008-04-21}}</ref> At the time of Matta-Clark's tenure there, Cornell's architecture program was guided in part by [[Colin Rowe]],<ref>[http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/1996/03/festschrift-honor-architecture-scholar-colin-rowe Cornell Festschrift honors Colin Rowe, one of architecture's most influential scholars] ''Cornell Chronicle'', 1996-03-2; accessed 2015-07-28</ref> a preeminent architectural theorist of modernism.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Petit|editor-first=Emmanuel|title=Reckoning with Colin Rowe: Ten Architects Take Position|date=2015|publisher=Routledge|location=New York}}</ref>\n\nMatta-Clark used a number of media to document his work, including film, video, and photography. His work includes performance and recycling pieces, space and texture works, and his \"building cuts\". He also used puns and other word games as a way to re-conceptualize preconditioned roles and relationships (of everything, from people to architecture). {{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\nIn February, 1969, the \"[[Earth Art]]\" show, curated by [[Willoughby Sharp]] at the invitation of Tom Leavitt, was realized at Andrew Dickson White Museum of Art, [[Cornell University]]. Matta-Clark, who lived in Ithaca at the time, was invited by Willoughby Sharp to help the artists in \"[[Earth Art]]\" with the on-site execution of their works for the exhibition. Sharp then encouraged Gordon Matta-Clark to move to New York City where Sharp continued to introduce him to members of the New York art world. Matta-Clark's work, ''Museum,'' at [[Klaus Kertess]]' [[Bykert Gallery]], was listed and illustrated on pages 4\u20135 of ''Avalanche'' 1, Fall 1970.\n\nIn 1971 Matta-Clark, [[Carol Goodden]], and [[Tina Girouard]] co-founded [[FOOD]], a restaurant in Manhattan's [[SoHo, New York| Soho]] neighborhood; managed and staffed by artists.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Waxman|first=Lori|title=The Banquet Years: FOOD, A SoHo Restaurant|journal=Gastronomica: The Journal of Food and Culture|date=2008|volume=8|issue=4|pages=24\u201333|doi=10.1525/gfc.2008.8.4.24}}</ref> The restaurant turned dining into an event with an open kitchen and exotic ingredients that celebrated cooking. The activities at FOOD helped delineate how the art community defined itself in downtown Manhattan.<ref name=\"GMCW\"/> The first of its kind in SoHo, Food became well known among artists and was a central meeting-place for groups such as the [[Philip Glass Ensemble]], [[Mabou Mines]], and the dancers of [[Grand Union (dance group)|Grand Union]]. He ran FOOD until 1973.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Gordon Matta-Clark|author=Steven Stern|magazine=Frieze Magazine|date=September 2007|url=https://frieze.com/article/gordon-matta-clark-0|accessdate=2017-07-10}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1970s and in the context of his artistic community surrounding FOOD, Matta-Clark developed the idea of \"anarchitecture\" - a conflation of the words anarchy and architecture - to suggest an interest in voids, gaps, and left-over spaces.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Rocking the Foundation|author=Jeff Rian|magazine=Frieze Magazine|date=June 1993|url=https://frieze.com/article/rocking-foundation|accessdate=2017-07-10}}</ref> With his project Fake Estates, Matta-Clark addressed these issues of non-sites by purchasing at auction 15 leftover and unusably small slivers of land in Queens and Staten Island, [[New York (state)|New York]], for $25\u2013$75 a plot. He documented them through photographs, maps, bureaucratic records and deeds, and spoke and wrote about them - but was not able to occupy these residual elements of zoning irregularities in any other way.<ref>{{cite book| editor-last=Kastner| editor-first=Jeffrey|editor2-last=Najafi|editor2-first=Sina|editor3-last=Richard|editor3-first=Frances|title=Odd Lots: Revisiting Gordon Matta-Clark's Fake Estates|publisher=Cabinet Books|year=2005|location=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title=Odd Lots: Revisiting Gordon Matta-Clark's Fake Estates| publisher=Cabinet| date=2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, he performed a literal [[deconstruction]], by removing the facade of a condemned house along the [[Love Canal]], and moving the resulting walls to [[Artpark]], in his work ''Bingo''.<ref>{{cite web|title=''Bingo Ninths''|format=video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OoUbs1-oSxI|accessdate=2008-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bingo|url=http://www.artfacts.net/index.php/pageType/exhibitionInfo/exhibition/15849/lang/2|accessdate=2008-10-26}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[Biennale de Paris]] in 1975, he made the piece titled Conical Intersect by cutting a large cone-shaped hole through two townhouses dating from the 17th century in the market district known as [[Les Halles]] which were to be knocked down in order to construct the then-controversial [[Centre Georges Pompidou]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Jenkins|first=Bruce|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: Conical Intersect|date=2011|publisher=Afterall Books|location=London}}</ref>\n\nFor his final major project, ''Circus or The Caribbean Orange'' (1978), Matta-Clark made circle cuts in the walls and floors of a townhouse next-door to the first [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago]], building (237 East Ontario Street), thus altering the space entirely.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.artdaily.com/index.asp?int_sec=11&int_new=22966&int_modo=2|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: You Are the Measure|work=Artdaily|year=2008|accessdate=2011-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcachicago.org/information/history.php?page=ihist|title=History of the MCA|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|accessdate=2011-06-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725013043/http://www.mcachicago.org/information/history.php?page=ihist|archivedate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his 1978 project, the MCA presented two retrospectives of Matta-Clark's work, in 1985 and in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mcachicago.org/Exhibitions/2008/Gordon-Matta-Clark-You-Are-The-Measure|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: You Are the Measure|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|accessdate=2017-07-10}}</ref> The 2008 exhibition ''You Are the Measure'' included never-before-displayed archival material of his 1978 Chicago project. ''You Are the Measure'' traveled to the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], New York, and the [[Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcachicago.org/media_uploads/releases/45b89Gordon.pdf|work=Press Release|date=2008-01-01|title=Gordon Matta-Clark: You Are the Measure|publisher=Museum of Contemporary Art, Chicago|accessdate=2011-06-13}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nMatta-Clark died from [[pancreatic cancer]] on August 27, 1978, aged 35, in [[New York, New York]].<ref>[http://www.davidzwirner.com/artists/gordon-matta-clark/biography Profile], davidzwirner.com; accessed March 28, 2015.</ref> He was survived by his widow, Jane Crawford. The Gordon Matta-Clark Archive is housed at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], Montreal.<ref>[https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/370196 Gordon Matta-Clark Archive], cca.qc.ca; accessed 2015-07-29.</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/03/03/arts/design/03matt.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 Profile], nytimes.com; accessed March 28, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Videography==\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=2169 ''Program One: Chinatown Voyeur'' (1971)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3495 ''Program Two'' (1971-1972)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13702 ''Tree Dance'' (1971)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13678 ''Open House'' (1972)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3791 ''Program Three'' (1971-1975)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13692 ''Fire Child'' (1971)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13841 ''Fresh Kill'' (1972)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13842 ''Day's End'' (1975)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=761 ''Food'' (1972)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3811 '' Program Five'' (1972-1976)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13843 ''Automation House'' (1972)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13844 ''Clockshower'' (1973)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13845 ''City Slivers'' (1976)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=1533 ''Program Four: Sauna View'' (1973)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=2925 ''Program Six'' (1974-1976)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13657 ''Splitting'' (1974)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13846 ''Bingo/Ninths'' (1974)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13847 ''Substrait (Underground Dailies)'' (1976)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=2359 ''Program Seven'' (1974-2005)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=13637 ''Conical Intersect\" (1975)]\n**[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=9797 ''Sous-Sols de Paris (Paris Underground)'' (1977-2005)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=12568 ''The Wall'' (1976-2007)]\n*[http://www.eai.org/title.htm?id=3313 ''Program Eight: Office Baroque'' (1977-2005)]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MoMA artist|6636}}\n*[https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search/details/collection/object/370196 Gordon Matta-Clark archive], cca.qc.ca\n*[http://www.davidzwirner.com/artists/4/press.htm Selected Press], DavidZwirner.com\n*[http://www.artnet.com/artist/11329/Gordon_Matta-Clark.html Profile], Artnet.com \n*[http://www.eai.org/artists/gordon-matta-clark/biography EAI: Gordon Matta-Clark Biography] and a list of [http://www.eai.org/artists/gordon-matta-clark/titles video works] by the artist\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matta-Clark, Gordon}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American people of Chilean descent]]\n[[Category:American conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pancreatic cancer]]\n[[Category:Deconstructivism]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n[[Category:Cornell University College of Architecture, Art, and Planning alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Veranam", "label": "safe", "comment": "Exhibitions", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_Matta-Clark"}
{"title_page": "Viktor Rosenzweig", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image        = Viktor Rosenzweig.JPG\n| imagesize    = 150px\n| name         = Viktor Rosenzweig \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = 1914\n| birth_place  = [[Ruma]], [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Empire]], (now [[Serbia]]n [[Vojvodina|Autonomous Province of Vojvodina]])\n| death_date   = 9 July 1941 (aged 27)\n| death_place  = [[Kerestinec]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], (now [[Croatia]])\n| death_cause  = Murdered in [[Holocaust]]\n| occupation   = [[Agronomy|Agronomist]]\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Zagreb]]\n| relations    = \n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| nationality  = [[Croats|Croat]]\n}}\n\n'''Viktor Rosenzweig''' (1914&ndash;1941) was a [[Croatia]]n [[Jew]]ish [[League of Communists of Croatia|communist]], poet and writer.<ref name=\"\u017ez\">{{harvtxt|Snje\u0161ka Kne\u017eevi\u0107|2011|p=115}}</ref><ref name=\"hz\">{{harvtxt|Ivo Goldstein|2001|pp=88, 271}}</ref>\n\nRosenzweig was born in [[Ruma]] in 1914. During high school education he became a member of the [[Young Communist League of Yugoslavia]] - '''SKOJ''' (from Serbo-Croatian: ''Savez komunisti\u010dke omladine Jugoslavije''). Rosenzweig studied and graduated from the Faculty of Agriculture at [[University of Zagreb]]. At the university he was one of the most observed and noticed [[Marxism|Marxist]] around. In 1934, he became a member of the [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia|Communist Party of Yugoslavia]]. In 1935, as a communist, he was sentenced to six months in prison. Rosenweig was a poet who wrote number of poems. Some of his poets were later published in a revolutionary writers collection \"Rije\u010di i Djela\" (''Words and Acts''). In April 1941, after [[Independent State of Croatia]] establishment, Rosenzweig was arrested and imprisoned at Savska cesta prison. On July 9, 1941 Rosenzweig was killed by [[Usta\u0161e]] together with [[Bo\u017eidar Ad\u017eija]], [[Otokar Ker\u0161ovani]], [[Ognjen Prica]] and [[Zvonimir Richtmann]].<ref name=\"\u017ez\"/><ref name=\"hz\"/>\n\n==Published works==\n* ''Na\u0161 \u017eivot'', Orbis Zagreb, 1939\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Snje\u0161ka Kne\u017eevi\u0107|first=Aleksander Laslo|title=\u017didovski Zagreb|year=2011|publisher=AGM, \u017didovska op\u0107ina Zagreb|location=Zagreb|isbn=978-953-174-393-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Goldstein|first=Ivo|title=Holokaust u Zagrebu|year=2001|publisher=Novi Liber|location=Zagreb|isbn=953-6045-19-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenzweig, Viktor}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ruma]]\n[[Category:Croatian Jews]]\n[[Category:Austro-Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Croatian Austro-Hungarians]]\n[[Category:Croatian people of Serbian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Croatian communists]]\n[[Category:Croatian male poets]]\n[[Category:Croatian civilians killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Agriculture, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish socialists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Croatian poets]]\n[[Category:Croatian Marxists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image        = Viktor Rosenzweig.JPG\n| imagesize    = 150px\n| name         = Viktor Rosenzweig \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = 1914\n| birth_place  = [[Ruma]], [[Austria-Hungary|Austro-Hungarian Empire]], (now [[Serbia]]n [[Vojvodina|Autonomous Province of Vojvodina]])\n| death_date   = 9 July 1941 (aged 27)\n| death_place  = [[Kerestinec]], [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia]], (now [[Croatia]])\n| death_cause  = Murdered in [[Holocaust]]\n| occupation   = [[Agronomy|Agronomist]]\n| alma_mater   = [[University of Zagreb]]\n| relations    = \n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| nationality  = [[Croats|Croat]]\n}}\n\n'''Viktor Rosenzweig''' (1914&ndash;1941) was a [[Croatia]]n [[Jew]]ish [[League of Communists of Croatia|communist]], poet and writer.<ref name=\"\u017ez\">{{harvtxt|Snje\u0161ka Kne\u017eevi\u0107|2011|p=115}}</ref><ref name=\"hz\">{{harvtxt|Ivo Goldstein|2001|pp=88, 271}}</ref>\n\nRosenzweig was born in [[Ruma]] in 1914. During high school education he became a member of the [[Young Communist League of Yugoslavia]] - '''SKOJ''' (from Serbo-Croatian: ''Savez komunisti\u010dke omladine Jugoslavije''). Rosenzweig studied and graduated from the Faculty of Agriculture at [[University of Zagreb]]. At the university he was one of the most observed and noticed [[Marxism|Marxist]] around. In 1934, he became a member of the [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia|Communist Party of Yugoslavia]]. In 1935, as a communist, he was sentenced to six months in prison. Rosenweig was a poet who wrote number of poems. Some of his poets were later published in a revolutionary writers collection \"Rije\u010di i Djela\" (''Words and Acts''). In April 1941, after [[Independent State of Croatia]] establishment, Rosenzweig was arrested and imprisoned at Savska cesta prison. On July 9, 1941 Rosenzweig was killed by [[Usta\u0161e]] together with [[Bo\u017eidar Ad\u017eija]], [[Otokar Ker\u0161ovani]], [[Ognjen Prica]] and [[Zvonimir Richtmann]].<ref name=\"\u017ez\"/><ref name=\"hz\"/>\n\n==Published works==\n* ''Na\u0161 \u017eivot'', Orbis Zagreb, 1939\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|last=Snje\u0161ka Kne\u017eevi\u0107|first=Aleksander Laslo|title=\u017didovski Zagreb|year=2011|publisher=AGM, \u017didovska op\u0107ina Zagreb|location=Zagreb|isbn=978-953-174-393-8|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Goldstein|first=Ivo|title=Holokaust u Zagrebu|year=2001|publisher=Novi Liber|location=Zagreb|isbn=953-6045-19-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenzweig, Viktor}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ruma]]\n[[Category:Croatian Jews]]\n[[Category:Austro-Hungarian Jews]]\n[[Category:Croatian Austro-Hungarians]]\n[[Category:Croatian people of Serbian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Croatian communists]]\n[[Category:Croatian male poets]]\n[[Category:Croatian civilians killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Croatia]]\n[[Category:Faculty of Agriculture, University of Zagreb alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish socialists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Croatian poets]]\n[[Category:Croatian Marxists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viktor_Rosenzweig"}
